{"title_page": "Womb (film)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Womb\n| image = Womb film.jpg\n| caption =\n| director = [[Benedek Fliegauf]]\n| producer =Gerhard Meixner<br /> Andr\u00e1s Muhi<br /> Roman Paul\n| writer = Benedek Fliegauf<br />Elizabeth Szasz\n| starring =  [[Eva Green]]<br />[[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]\n| music =[[Max Richter]]\n| cinematography =Peter Szatmari\n| editing =Xavier Box\n| distributor =Olive Films\n| released = {{Film date|2010|7|15|German Film Week}}\n| runtime = 107 min.\n| country = Germany, Hungary, France\n| language = English\n| budget = $\u20ac3,660,000 (estimated)\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Womb''''' (retitled '''''Clone''''' for its UK DVD release) is a 2010 science fiction [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Benedek Fliegauf]] and starring [[Eva Green]] and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe film commences with a pregnant woman ([[Eva Green]]) telling her unborn child that the father has departed for good, but that together they will start a new life. A love story is then told between two children, Rebecca and Tommy, who swear each other eternal love. When Rebecca departs suddenly for Japan with her mother, the two are separated. Twelve years later, Rebecca returns as a young woman to find that Tommy (Matt Smith) not only remembers her, but still cares deeply for her. The two begin a new relationship.\n\nTommy is a political activist fighting against the [[biotechnology|biotech]] corporations, who plan to open a new natural park populated by animals artificially created by [[cloning]]. Tommy plans to spoil the inauguration ceremony by letting loose rucksacks filled with cockroaches. Rebecca, herself a computer programmer of leak detection sonar software for underground storage containers, insists on accompanying Tommy.\n\nDriving to the site of the new natural park through a lonely wilderness, Rebecca asks Tommy to stop the car so that she can relieve herself at the side of the road. Meantime, Tommy leaves the car and is struck and killed suddenly by a passing vehicle.\n\nRebecca and Tommy's parents are stricken with grief. Rebecca wants to use new scientific advancements to have Tommy cloned and thereby bring him back to life. She offers to be impregnated using Tommy's DNA. Though Tommy's mother objects, his father agrees to give Rebecca Tommy's cell material, but urges her to think through her decision carefully before proceeding. Rebecca, however, continues and gives birth to a new Tommy by [[Caesarean section]].\n\nTommy is now raised as Rebecca's son, and the two have a close relationship. Rebecca presents to him a [[pleo]], an artificial living animal created using new biotechnology. Tommy and his playmates observe a neighbourhood girl and try to determine if she has a \"copy smell\" as the girl is a clone. The neighbourhood mothers display prejudice against \"copies\", expecting Rebecca to not let Tommy associate with them. Rebecca, though horrified, agrees in order not to isolate her son. Eventually rumours about Tommy spread, and Tommy is forced to celebrate his birthday alone with his mother, his playmates all being barred from attending by their mothers.\n\nRebecca moves to a more remote location with Tommy. Tommy begins to ask questions about his father, wanting to know how his father died. He buries the pleo his mother gave him for his birthday while out playing with his friend. His mother finds out and gives him back the pleo, which is now no longer working.\n\nYears later, Tommy has grown as old as his original was when he died. As a result, he starts to manifest certain personality traits and interests of the original Tommy (such as his interests in biology). He is now the adult son of still-youthful Rebecca. When Tommy brings a girlfriend, Monica, home to stay with them Rebecca behaves jealously, to both Tommy's and Monica's bewilderment. Tommy struggles with what appears to be sexual tension [[Oedipus complex|between himself and his mother]]. The original Tommy's mother, now an old woman, arrives unexpectedly and stares silently at Tommy, who feels he recognizes the stranger. Frightened and frustrated by Rebecca's lack of explanation, Tommy lashes out at Rebecca, ignoring Monica, who quickly departs.\n\nAn angry Tommy demands answers from his mother, Rebecca, who gives him original Tommy's old laptop with pictures of himself and his real mother and father (the former he met earlier). Tommy, out of confusion and sexual tension, initiates sex with Rebecca. From the blood on her hand, it is implied he took her virginity in the process. The next day Tommy packs his things, then addresses Rebecca by her first name (and not as \"Mom\") and thanks her for the life he's had and then leaves.  The pregnant Rebecca, from the film's first scene, is carrying Tommy's(the clone Tommy's) child.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Eva Green]] as Rebecca\n*[[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] as Thomas \"Tommy\", and the older clone of Thomas\n*[[Lesley Manville]] as Judith\n*[[Peter Wight (actor)|Peter Wight]] as Ralph\n*[[Istv\u00e1n L\u00e9n\u00e1rt]] as Henry\n*[[Hannah Murray]] as Monica\n*[[Ruby O. Fee]] as Rebecca (child)\n*[[Tristan Christopher]] as Thomas (child)\n*[[Natalia Tena]] as Rose\n*[[Ingo Hasselbach]] as Walter\n*[[Ella Smith (actress)|Ella Smith]] as Molly\n*[[Gina Alice Stiebitz]] as Dima\n*[[Wunmi Mosaku]] as Erica\n*[[Amanda Lawrence]] as Teacher\n*[[Jennifer Lim (British actress)|Jennifer Lim]] as Mrs. Muju 2\n\n== Production ==\nThe film was shot in [[Germany]] on the islands of [[Langene\u00df]] and [[Sylt]] and in [[Sankt Peter-Ording]], [[Hamburg]] and [[Berlin]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb (2010)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1216520/locations|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has received a rating of 35%, based on 20 reviews, with an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/womb|language=en|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 48 out of 100, based on 8 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/womb|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1216520|Womb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Womb}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Max Richter]]\n[[Category:Films about cloning]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Hungarian films]]\n[[Category:Incest in film]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Womb\n| image = Womb film.jpg\n| caption =\n| director = [[Benedek Fliegauf]]\n| producer =Gerhard Meixner<br /> Andr\u00e1s Muhi<br /> Roman Paul\n| writer = Benedek Fliegauf<br />Elizabeth Szasz\n| starring =  [[Eva Green]]<br />[[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]\n| music =[[Max Richter]]\n| cinematography =Peter Szatmari\n| editing =Xavier Box\n| distributor =Olive Films\n| released = {{Film date|2010|7|15|German Film Week}}\n| runtime = 107 min.\n| country = Germany, Hungary, France\n| language = English\n| budget = $\u20ac3,660,000 (estimated)\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Womb''''' (retitled '''''Clone''''' for its UK DVD release) is a 2010 science fiction [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Benedek Fliegauf]] and starring [[Eva Green]] and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe film commences with a pregnant woman ([[Eva Green]]) telling her unborn child that the father has departed for good, but that together they will start a new life. A love story is then told between two children, Rebecca and Tommy, who swear each other eternal love. When Rebecca departs suddenly for Japan with her mother, the two are separated. Twelve years later, Rebecca returns as a young woman to find that Tommy (Matt Smith) not only remembers her, but still cares deeply for her. The two begin a new relationship.\n\nTommy is a political activist fighting against the [[biotechnology|biotech]] corporations, who plan to open a new natural park populated by animals artificially created by [[cloning]]. Tommy plans to spoil the inauguration ceremony by letting loose rucksacks filled with cockroaches. Rebecca, herself a computer programmer of leak detection sonar software for underground storage containers, insists on accompanying Tommy.\n\nDriving to the site of the new natural park through a lonely wilderness, Rebecca asks Tommy to stop the car so that she can relieve herself at the side of the road. Meantime, Tommy leaves the car and is struck and killed suddenly by a passing vehicle.\n\nRebecca and Tommy's parents are stricken with grief. Rebecca wants to use new scientific advancements to have Tommy cloned and thereby bring him back to life. She offers to be impregnated using Tommy's DNA. Though Tommy's mother objects, his father agrees to give Rebecca Tommy's cell material, but urges her to think through her decision carefully before proceeding. Rebecca, however, continues and gives birth to a new Tommy by [[Caesarean section]].\n\nTommy is now raised as Rebecca's son, and the two have a close relationship. Rebecca presents to him a [[pleo]], an artificial living animal created using new biotechnology. Tommy and his playmates observe a neighbourhood girl and try to determine if she has a \"copy smell\" as the girl is a clone. The neighbourhood mothers display prejudice against \"copies\", expecting Rebecca to not let Tommy associate with them. Rebecca, though horrified, agrees in order not to isolate her son. Eventually rumours about Tommy spread, and Tommy is forced to celebrate his birthday alone with his mother, his playmates all being barred from attending by their mothers.\n\nRebecca moves to a more remote location with Tommy. Tommy begins to ask questions about his father, wanting to know how his father died. He buries the pleo his mother gave him for his birthday while out playing with his friend. His mother finds out and gives him back the pleo, which is now no longer working.\n\nYears later, Tommy has grown as old as his original was when he died. As a result, he starts to manifest certain personality traits and interests of the original Tommy (such as his interests in biology). He is now the adult son of still-youthful Rebecca. When Tommy brings a girlfriend, Monica, home to stay with them Rebecca behaves jealously, to both Tommy's and Monica's bewilderment. Tommy struggles with what appears to be sexual tension [[Oedipus complex|between himself and his mother]]. The original Tommy's mother, now an old woman, arrives unexpectedly and stares silently at Tommy, who feels he recognizes the stranger. Frightened and frustrated by Rebecca's lack of explanation, Tommy lashes out at Rebecca, ignoring Monica, who quickly departs.\n\nAn angry Tommy demands answers from his mother, Rebecca, who gives him original Tommy's old laptop with pictures of himself and his real mother and father (the former he met earlier). Tommy, out of confusion and sexual tension, initiates sex with Rebecca. From the blood on her hand, it is implied he took her virginity in the process. The next day Tommy packs his things, then addresses Rebecca by her first name (and not as \"Mom\") and thanks her for the life he's had and then leaves.  The pregnant Rebecca, from the film's first scene, is carrying Tommy's(the clone Tommy\u2019s) child.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Eva Green]] as Rebecca\n*[[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] as Thomas \"Tommy\", and the older clone of Thomas\n*[[Lesley Manville]] as Judith\n*[[Peter Wight (actor)|Peter Wight]] as Ralph\n*[[Istv\u00e1n L\u00e9n\u00e1rt]] as Henry\n*[[Hannah Murray]] as Monica\n*[[Ruby O. Fee]] as Rebecca (child)\n*[[Tristan Christopher]] as Thomas (child)\n*[[Natalia Tena]] as Rose\n*[[Ingo Hasselbach]] as Walter\n*[[Ella Smith (actress)|Ella Smith]] as Molly\n*[[Gina Alice Stiebitz]] as Dima\n*[[Wunmi Mosaku]] as Erica\n*[[Amanda Lawrence]] as Teacher\n*[[Jennifer Lim (British actress)|Jennifer Lim]] as Mrs. Muju 2\n\n== Production ==\nThe film was shot in [[Germany]] on the islands of [[Langene\u00df]] and [[Sylt]] and in [[Sankt Peter-Ording]], [[Hamburg]] and [[Berlin]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb (2010)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1216520/locations|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has received a rating of 35%, based on 20 reviews, with an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/womb|language=en|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 48 out of 100, based on 8 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Womb|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/womb|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1216520|Womb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Womb}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Max Richter]]\n[[Category:Films about cloning]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Hungarian films]]\n[[Category:Incest in film]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Womb_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Yahya Jammeh", "text_new": "{{short description|2nd President of the Gambia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Yahya Jammeh\n|image         = Yahya Jammeh.jpg\n|office        = [[List of heads of state of the Gambia|2nd]] [[President of the Gambia]]\n|vicepresident = [[Isatou Njie-Saidy]]\n|term_start    = 6 November 1996\n|term_end      = 19 January 2017{{efn|Jammeh's term was originally scheduled to end on 19 January 2017, however, the Parliament extended his presidential term for three months, and he refused to relinquish power until 21 January when he was forced to step down after a [[ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia|regional military intervention]]. Adama Barrow nevertheless took his oath at The Gambian Embassy in Senegal on January 19th.}}\n|predecessor   = [[Dawda Jawara]]\n|successor     = [[Adama Barrow]]\n|office1        = [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council|Chairman of the Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]]\n|deputy1 = F. D. Sabali\n|term_start1    = 22 July 1994\n|term_end1      = 6 November 1996\n|predecessor1   = ''Position established''\n|successor1     = ''Position abolished''\n|birth_name    = Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jammeh\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=y|1965|5|25}}\n|birth_place   = [[Kanilai]], [[The Gambia (1965-1970)|Gambia]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Tuti Faal|1994|1998|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|[[Zeinab Jammeh|Zeinab Soumah]]|1999}}<br />{{marriage|Alima Sallah|2010|2011|reason=div}}\n|children      = 2\n|allegiance    = {{flag|The Gambia}}\n|branch        = National Gendarmerie<br />National Army\n|serviceyears  = 1984\u20131996\n|rank          = [[Colonel]]\n|commands      = National Gendarmerie\n}}\n'''Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jemus Junkung Jammeh''' (born 25 May 1965) is a Gambian politician and former military officer who was the leader of [[The Gambia]] from 1994 to 2017, firstly as chairman of the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]] (AFPRC) from 1994 to 1996 and then as [[President of the Gambia]] from 1996 to 2017.\n\nJammeh was born in [[Kanilai]], and is a [[Muslim]] of the [[Jola people|Jola ethnic group]]. He attended Gambia High School in [[Banjul]] from 1978 to 1983 and served in the [[Gambia Armed Forces|Gambia National Gendarmerie]] from 1984 to 1989. He was then commissioned as an officer of the [[Military of the Gambia|Gambia National Army]], commanding the Military Police from 1992 to 1994. In July 1994, he led a bloodless [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'etat]] that overthrew the government of [[Dawda Jawara]] and installed himself as chairman of AFPRC, a military junta, and ruled by decree until his [[1996 Gambian presidential election|election]] as president in 1996.\n\nJammeh was re-elected as president [[2001 Gambian presidential election|in 2001]], [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006]] and [[2011 Gambian presidential election|2011]], but lost to [[Adama Barrow]] [[2016 Gambian presidential election|in 2016]]. His time in office saw the authoritarian oppression of anti-government journalists, [[LGBT rights in the Gambia|LGBT people]] and opposition parties. His foreign policy led to a constantly strained relationship with the sole neighbouring country of [[Senegal]]. In 2013, Jammeh withdrew the Gambia from the [[Commonwealth of Nations]], and in 2016 he began the process of withdrawing it from the [[International Criminal Court]] (later rescinded by the Barrow government).\n\nJammeh is accused of having stolen millions of dollars from the country's coffers to fund a life of luxury. After leaving office, his assets were frozen by many countries and he went into exile. In addition to charges of corruption and human rights violations, he is also accused of having raped a number of young women.\n\n== Early life and military service ==\n\nJammeh was born on 25 May 1965 in [[Kanilai]], a village in the [[Foni Kansala]] district of the [[West Coast Division (Gambia)|Western Division]] of The Gambia. He is the son of Aja Fatou Ashombi Bojang, a housewife and trader, and Abdul Aziz James Junkung Jammeh, a career wrestler. Jammeh's grandparents migrated to the Gambia from the [[Casamance]] region of [[Senegal]].<ref>M'Bai, p. 90</ref> He had a rural upbringing as part of a [[Muslim]] [[Jola people|Jola]] family, primarily focused in Kanilai. One of his closest childhood friends was reportedly Mustapha James Kujabi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/the-gambian-dictator-who-kills-his-own-family-members-to-stay-in-power/|title=The Gambian Dictator Who Kills His Own Family Members To Stay In Power|last=|first=|date=4 September 2015|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref> He attended Kanilai primary school, Saint Edwards primary school in [[Bwiam]], from 1972 to 1978. Due to his result in the common entrance (CE) exam, he was awarded a government scholarship to [[Gambia Senior Secondary School|Gambia High School]] in [[Banjul]], in 1978. His formal education ended after he received his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O Levels]] in 1983.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/28/world/in-gambia-new-coup-follows-old-pattern.html|title=In Gambia, New Coup Follows Old Pattern|last=French|first=Howard W.|date=28 August 1994|work=The New York Times|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-takes-nomination-turn-at-iec-today|title=President Jammeh takes nomination turn at IEC today|last=|first=|date=10 November 2016|work=The Point|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Hughes and Perfect, pp. 109-111</ref>{{Quote box\n|quote = In those days, he used to defend the rights of many Gendarmes who for one reason or another had felt apart with the Gendarmerie command and administration and were brought to the [Military Police] for either investigation or punishment. What actually makes him changed into the biggest violator of the human and civic rights of ordinary Gambian citizens is beyond my comprehension|source = |width = 25%|author = Capt. Bunja Darboe (rtd)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jollofnews.com/2016/07/26/gambia-why-am-i-speaking-now/|title=Why Am I Speaking Now?|last=Darboe|first=Bunja|date=12 July 2016|work=Jollof News|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 1984, Jammeh joined what was then the Gambian National Gendarmerie as a private. He was part of the Special Intervention Unit from 1984 to 1986 and was an escort training instructor at the Gendarmerie Training School from 1986 to 1989. He was promoted to sergeant in April 1986, and to cadet officer in December 1987.<ref name=\":1\" /> A former Gendarmerie officer, Binneh S. Minteh, later claimed that Jammeh \"had always singled out Mandinka\u2019s as bad people\" during his time as a Gendarme. In particular, Minteh recalled Jammeh's \"ruthless and disrespectful encounter\" with sergeant major Kebba Dibba, and when he \"brandished a pistol and threatened to shoot\" Captain Ebrima Camara simply on the basis of their ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gainako.com/president-jammehs-threats-mandinkas-gambia-irresponsible-repugnant-national-leader/|title=President Jammeh's Threats against Mandinka's in Gambia are Irresponsible and Repugnant of a National Leader|last=Minteh|first=Binneh S.|date=16 June 2016|work=Gainako|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined the Gambia National Army and was commissioned as a second lieutenant on 29 September 1989, serving as the officer in charge (OIC) of the Presidential Escort, part of the Presidential Guards, from 1989 to 1990. In 1991, he served as the officer commanding (OC) the Mobile Gendarmerie, and from 1992 to 1994 was the OC of the Gambia National Army Military Police. On 1 February 1992, he had been promoted to lieutenant. Jammeh was the head of security detail attached to [[Pope John Paul II]] during his visit to the Gambia in February 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/the-man-who-provided-security-to-the-late-pope-john-paul-the-ii-in-february-of-1992-later-toppled-jawara-from-power/|title=The Man Who Provided Security To The Late Pope John Paul, the II, In February Of 1992, Later Toppled Jawara From Power|last=|first=|date=3 August 2015|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> He attended the [[Military Police Officers Basic Course]] (MPOBC) at [[Fort McClellan]] in the [[United States]] from September 1993 to January 1994.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== 1994 coup d'etat and military rule ==\n\n=== 1994 coup d'etat ===\nJammeh was one of the four junior Army officers who organised the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'etat]] against [[Dawda Jawara]]'s government. The other three were Sana Sabally, [[Sadibou Hydara]] and Edward Singhateh. The coup, which took place on 22 July, was successful and bloodless, leading to Jawara fleeing into exile.<ref name=\":3\">Hughes and Perfect, p. xxix</ref> Four days later, on 26 July, the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]] (AFPRC) was formed with Jammeh as its chairman.<ref name=\":2\" /> Jammeh promised that it would be a \"coup with a difference\", and that the country would be returned to civilian rule \"as soon as we have set things right\". One result of the coup was that the [[European Union]] and the United States, the major donors of foreign aid to the Gambia, suspended their aid programmes until the country was returned to civil rule. Jammeh claimed the suspension of aid programmes amounted to \"[[neocolonialism]]\". A Western diplomat who spoke to ''[[The New York Times]]'' said, \"This is exactly the same phenomenon we have seen elsewhere, with the only difference being that so far there has been no violence.\" In particular, the coup was compared with [[Samuel Doe]]'s in the [[Liberia]], which led to the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe 1994 coup d'etat in the Gambia, overthrowing the government of Dawda Jawara, represented a buck in the post-1989 sub-Saharan Africa trend away from authoritarianism and towards multiparty politics. The Gambia had represented an anomaly in Africa as one of the few countries that had a functioning democracy prior to 1989.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edie|first=Carlene, J.|year=2000|title=Democracy in the Gambia: Past, Present and Prospects for the Future|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/ad/article/viewFile/22106/19406|journal=Africa Development|volume=XXV|pages=161\u2013198|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Rule through the AFPRC ===\nIn the aftermath of the coup, Jammeh governed by decree alongside four other junior officers and several civilians. He banned all political activity, arrested two socialist journalists, and detained several of his Army superiors. He also confined ministers of Jawara's government to [[house arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On 17 October, Jammeh announced that there would be a four-year transition to civilian government. In November 1994, the same month when Jammeh was formally promoted to the rank of captain, there was an unsuccessful coup attempt by several disaffected young officers leading in numerous deaths, but Jammeh remained in power. The National Consultative Committee (NCC) was appointed on 7 December to review the transition process, and when they reported on 27 January 1995, they recommended a two-year transition period. The same day as the NCC's report, two of the original coup leaders, Sabally and Hydara, launched an unsuccessful attempt to overthrow Jammeh as chairman. Subsequently, Singhateh was appointed as vice-chairman of the AFPRC, and Hydara died in prison on 3 June.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Constitutional Review Commission (CRC) was appointed in April 1995 and reported to the government in November 1995. Its report was published in March 1996 was put to a [[1996 Gambian constitutional referendum|national referendum]] on 8 August 1996. The new constitution, which provided for multiparty elections, an unlimited number of five-year presidential terms, and a lowering of the voting age from 21 to 18, was approved by a majority of 70%. According to Saine, Jammeh would \"[enjoy] unrivalled political and economic power as a consequence of the new constitution. In contrast, opposition political parties [would be] sidelined and allowed little political space in a one-sided electoral contest in which Jammeh was the assured \u2018winner\u2019.\"<ref name=\":42\">Saine, p. 261</ref> Decree no. 89, issued on 14 August, reiterated the ban on the [[People's Progressive Party (Gambia)|PPP]], the [[National Convention Party (Gambia)|NCP]] and the [[Gambian People's Party|GPP]], but lifted the ban on the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism|PDOIS]] and the [[Gambia Party for Democracy and Progress|PDP]]. In 1996, on 28 August, Jammeh was formally promoted to the rank of colonel and then retired from the army on 6 September, one month before the 1996 presidential election.<ref name=\":3\" /> His retirement was marked by a ceremony that was described as \"actually a political event made palatable by a patina of military pomp.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/96BANJUL2256_a.html|title=Chairman Jammeh Retires From The Army - As A Colonel|last=|first=|date=13 September 1996|website=Wikileaks|access-date=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== President of the Gambia ==\n\n=== 1996 and 1997 elections ===\nJammeh won the [[1996 Gambian presidential election|1996 presidential election]] as the APRC candidate, winning 56% of the vote and beating [[Ousainou Darboe]], [[Hamat Bah]] and [[Sidia Jatta]]. Darboe was forced to seek refuge in the Senegalese embassy in Banjul, fearing an assassination plot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/WORLD/9609/28/newsbriefs/|title=Gambia army ruler wins election|last=|first=|date=28 September 1996|work=CNN|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> In the [[1997 Gambian parliamentary election|1997 parliamentary election]], the first to the new National Assembly put in place by the 1996 constitution, the APRC won a majority of seats. However, these two elections, the first following the transition from military to civil rule, were \"marred by provisions of the new, doctored constitution, an electoral commission appointed by Jammeh alone in 1995 and a political network that included the Green Boys \u2013 a now-disbanded vigilante group that was mobilised to intimidate the electorate to ensure Jammeh\u2019s \u2018victory\u2019.\" Saine argues that this combination of intimidation and harassment of the opposition, an inherent bias provided by the 1996 constitution, as well as a distinct financial advantage, meant that \"the presidential and national assembly elections were lost long before the first ballot was cast.\"<ref name=\":42\"/>\n\n=== Elections ===\nJammeh founded the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]] as his political party. He was elected as president in September 1996.<ref name=USBackground>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/5459.htm Background Note: The Gambia], U.S. Department of State, 22 April 2011.</ref> Foreign observers did not deem these elections free and fair.<ref name=USBackground /> He was re-elected on 18 October 2001 with about 53% of the vote; this election was generally deemed free and fair by observers,<ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2001/af/8377.htm Country Report on Human Rights Practices for The Gambia], U.S. Department of State, 4 March 2002.</ref> despite some very serious shortcomings ranging from overt government intimidation of voters to technical innovations (such as raising the required deposit to stand for election by a factor of 25) to distort the process in favour of the incumbent regime.<ref>\"Democratization in Africa\" by Diamond and Plattner (ed), Johns Hopkins University Press (1999), pages 216\u2013227 [https://books.google.com/books?id=olOGLS8yPREC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=&f=false]</ref>\n\nA coup attempt against Jammeh was reported to have been thwarted on 21 March 2006; Jammeh, who was in [[Mauritania]] at the time, quickly returned home. Army chief of staff Col. Ndure Cham, the alleged leader of the plot,<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=52380&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=GAMBIA \"Attempted coup averted, government says\"], IRIN, 22 March 2006.</ref> reportedly fled to neighbouring [[Senegal]], while other alleged conspirators were arrested<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4852190.stm \"Arrests over Gambia 'coup plot'\"], BBC News, 28 March 2006.</ref> and were put on trial for treason.<ref>[http://www.afrol.com/articles/21796 \"Suspected Gambian coupists before court martial\"], Afrol News, 6 October 2006.</ref> In April 2007, ten former officers accused of involvement were convicted and given prison sentences; four of them were sentenced to life in prison.<ref>[https://archive.today/20070517203204/http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=nw20070419213835762C477763 \"Gambia jails army coup plotters\"], Reuters (''IOL''), 20 April 2007.</ref>\n\nJammeh ran for a third term in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|presidential election]] held on 22 September 2006; the election was initially planned for October but was moved forward because of the Muslim holy month of [[Ramadan]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5352242.stm \"Q&A: Gambia votes\"], BBC News, 21 September 2006.</ref> He was re-elected with 67.3% of the vote and was declared the winner of the election; the opposition candidate [[Ousainou Darboe]] finished second, as in 2001.<ref name=\"winner\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5369040.stm \"Gambian president is re-elected\"], BBC News, 23 September 2006.</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Jammeh was again re-elected as president for a fourth term in office, reportedly having received 72% of the popular vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-15897134|title=Gambia president wins fourth term|date=2011-11-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic policy ===\n\n==== Suppression of the press ====\nOne of Jammeh's consistent targets throughout his time as President was the press and the media, as a whole as well as individual journalists. In 1998, the independent Citizen FM radio station was forced to close after a number of its staff were arrested and its equipment was confiscated. After its American proprietor sold it to a businessman with close ties to Jammeh in 1999, ''[[The Daily Observer]]'' became notably pro-Jammeh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2000/03/attacks-on-the-press-1999-the-gambia.php|title=Attacks on the Press 1999: The Gambia|last=|first=|date=22 March 2000|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> In August 2000, the anti-government Radio 1 FM suffered an arson attack.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2001/03/attacks-on-the-press-2000-the-gambia.php|title=Attacks on the Press 2000: The Gambia|last=|first=|date=2001|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref> [[Gambian Americans|Gambian American]] author Abdoulaye Saine states that Jammeh was able to use [[Gambia Radio & Television Service]] as his personal propaganda outlet whenever he required.<ref name=\":62\">Saine, p. 263</ref>\n\nJammeh has made a number of public statements against the press. In July 2000, he said that \"anybody bent on disturbing the peace and stability of the nation [should] be buried six feet deep.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> In April 2004, Jammeh told journalists to obey his government \"or go to hell\". In June 2005, he said that he had allowed \"too much freedom of expression\" in the Gambia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061127093825/http://www.rsf.org/IMG/pdf/Page_16_6.pdf Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jemus Junkung Jammeh], Reporters Without Borders.</ref>\n\nIn response to his suppression of the press and media in the Gambia, various online newspapers and radio stations were established by self-exiled Gambian journalists to publicise alleged government atrocities. These include ''Freedom Newspaper'', ''The Gambia Echo'' and ''Gainako''.<ref name=\":62\"/>\n\nJammeh also saw through legislation to restrict the activities of the press. The Newspaper Act 1994 imposed criminal penalties on private publications that failed to pay a yearly registration fee. The National Media Communication Act 2000 forced journalists to reveal confidential sources to police and the judiciary on demand.<ref name=\":8\" /> In December 2004, the Criminal Code (Amendment) Bill 2004 allowed prison terms for defamation and sedition. The same month, the Newspaper (Amendment) Bill 2004 required newspaper proprietors to purchase expensive operating licenses and forcing them to register their homes as [[Security (finance)|security]].\n\nA number of individual journalists were also targeted. In December 2004, [[Deyda Hydara]], then editor of [[The Point (the Gambia)|''The Point'']], announced his intention to publicly challenge newly-introduced legislation restricting press freedoms.  He was shot and killed when driving home in Banjul on 16 December, leading to thousands protesting on the streets.<ref name=\"auto3\">[http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=52505 \"Thousands protest peacefully at murder of journalist\"], IRIN, 22 December 2004.</ref> Some pointed at the government, led by Jammeh, as the murderers, but it has remained unsolved.<ref name=\"auto3\" /> Furthermore, in July 2006, [[Ebrima Manneh]] of ''The Daily Observer'' was arrested by state security after attempting to publish a [[BBC]] report critical of Jammeh. His arrest was witnessed by his coworkers,<ref name=\"CFP2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpj.org/2009/04/gambia-must-account-for-missing-journalist-ebrima.php|title=Gambia must account for missing journalist Ebrima Manneh|date=14 April 2009|publisher=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and, despite being ordered to release Manneh by an ECOWAS court, the government denied that Manneh was still imprisoned.<ref name=\"AFP2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5izABjky1HY0Bz47DUuc3V3SaNLGQ|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420053701/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5izABjky1HY0Bz47DUuc3V3SaNLGQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 April 2009|title=Missing Gambia journalist is dead: police|date=14 April 2009|agency=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=18 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> An unnamed police source said that he believed Manneh \"is no longer alive\".<ref name=\"AFP2\" /> Both [[Amnesty International]] and the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] have called for his release.<ref name=\"CFP2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|title=Ebrima Manneh|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|accessdate=17 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429082908/http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|archivedate=29 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's rights ====\nIn December 2015, Jammeh banned [[female genital mutilation]] (FGM) in The Gambia, labelling the practice of FGM as having \"no place in Islam or in modern society\"; anyone that ignored the ban would face a prison sentence of up to three years. After the end of [[Ramadan]] and [[Eid ul-Fitr]] in July 2016, Jammeh further announced a ban on [[child marriages]]. In 2016, some 30% of women were married while under the age of 18. Yahya Jammeh's response was that anyone caught marrying a girl under 18 years of age would be jailed for up to twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36746174|title=Gambia and Tanzania outlaw child marriage|date=8 July 2016|accessdate=26 November 2016|via=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==== Judiciary ====\nAs President, Jammeh had significant influence over the judiciary in the Gambia, particularly because Section 98 of the 1996 constitution permits the President to appoint judges directly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrlibrary.umn.edu/research/gambia-constitution.pdf|title=Constitution of the Republic of the Gambia|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Minnesota Human Rights Library|access-date=}}</ref> Saine argues that Jammeh's employment of mainly foreign judges allows him to effectively issue tough sentences to reduce dissent and to imprison both real and perceived threats to the president's power.<ref name=\":52\">Saine, p. 262</ref>\n\n==== LGBT rights ====\n{{See also|LGBT rights in the Gambia}}\nOn 15 May 2008, Jammeh announced that his government would introduce legislation that would set laws against homosexuals that would be \"stricter than those in [[Iran]]\", and that he would \"cut off the head\" of any gay or lesbian person discovered in the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\">[http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambia-News-President-Jammeh-Gives-Ultimatum-for-Homosexuals-to-.html President Jammeh Gives Ultimatum for Homosexuals to Leave] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315181156/http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambia-News-President-Jammeh-Gives-Ultimatum-for-Homosexuals-to-.html |date=15 March 2012 }}, Gambia News, 19 May 2008.</ref> News reports indicated his government intended to execute all homosexuals in the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\" /> In a speech given in Tallinding, Jammeh gave a \"final ultimatum\" to any gays or lesbians in the Gambia, warning them to leave the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\" /> In a speech to the United Nations on 27 September 2013, Jammeh said \"[h]omosexuality in all its forms and manifestations which, though very evil, antihuman as well as anti-Allah, is being promoted as a human right by some powers,\" who \"want to put an end to human existence.\"<ref name=\"JamehHomosexualityII2\">[https://news.yahoo.com/gambian-president-says-gays-threat-human-existence-20130928-122519635.html Gambian president says gays a threat to human existence-20130928], Reuters, 28 September 2013.</ref> On 18 February 2014, Jammeh called homosexuals \"vermins\" by saying that: \"We will fight these vermins [''sic''] called homosexuals or gays the same way we are fighting malaria-causing mosquitoes, if not more aggressively\". He also went on to disparage the [[LGBT]] by saying that \"As far as I am concerned, LGBT can only stand for [[Leprosy]], [[Gonorrhoea]], Bacteria and [[Tuberculosis]], all of which are detrimental to human existence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/18/us-gambia-homosexuality-idUSBREA1H1S820140218|title=Gambia's Jammeh calls gays 'vermin', says to fight like mosquitoes|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21623667-many-places-attacking-rights-gay-people-can-still-be-politically-useful-and|title=Tainting love|date=11 October 2014|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, in defiance of western criticism Jammeh intensified his anti-gay rhetoric, telling a crowd during an agricultural tour: \"If you do it [in the Gambia] I will slit your throat \u2013 if you are a man and want to marry another man in this country and we catch you, no one will ever set eyes on you again, and no white person can do anything about it.\"<ref>[https://news.vice.com/article/gambian-president-says-he-will-slit-gay-mens-throats-in-public-speech Gambian President Says He Will Slit Gay Men's Throats in Public Speech], [[Vice News]], 11 May 2015</ref>\n\nThis prompted a fresh round of condemnation from international human rights leaders. [[National Security Advisor (United States)|US National Security Advisor]] [[Susan Rice]] released a statement of condemnation on 16 May 2015: \"We condemn his comments, and note these threats come amid an alarming deterioration of the broader human rights situation in The Gambia,\" said Rice. \"We are deeply concerned about credible reports of torture, suspicious disappearances \u2013 including of two American citizens \u2013 and arbitrary detention at the government's hands.\"<ref>[http://www.washingtonblade.com/2015/05/16/susan-rice-condemns-gambia-presidents-anti-gay-comments/ U.S. slams Gambia president's anti-gay comments], ''[[Washington Blade]]'', 16 May 2015</ref>\n\n==== HIV/AIDS policy ====\nIn January 2007, Jammeh claimed he could cure [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[asthma]] with natural herbs.<ref name=\"BBCHIV\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6323449.stm \"President's 'HIV cure' condemned\"], BBC News, 2 February 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Observer41\">[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-discharges-41-hivaids-treated-patients President Jammeh discharges 41 HIV/AIDS treated patients] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727171859/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-discharges-41-hivaids-treated-patients |date=27 July 2011 }}, ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 12 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/19/gambia-witchcraft-hallucinogenics|title=Gambian state kidnaps 1,000 villagers in mass purge of 'witchcraft'|last=Rice|first=Xan|date=2009-03-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> His claimed treatment program includes instructing patients to cease taking their anti-retroviral drugs.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2007-02-20-gambia_x.htm Gambian president's claim of AIDS cure causes alarm], ''[[USA Today]]'', 20 February 2007.</ref><ref>Dibba, L. M., [http://allafrica.com/stories/200701190658.html Jammeh starts curing HIV/AIDS patients today], ''The Daily Observer'' (Banjul), 18 January 2007.</ref> His claims have been criticised for promoting unscientific treatment that could have dangerous results, including the infection of others by those who thought they had been cured by the method.<ref name=\"BBCHIV\" /><ref name=\"Observer41\" /> In December 2011, he restated during an interview that the alleged cure for HIV/AIDS was \"going very well\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16144116 \"Gambia President Yahya Jammeh: Critics 'can go to hell'\"], BBC News, 12 December 2011</ref>\n\nFadzai Gwaradzimba, the country representative of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] in the Gambia, was told to leave the country after she expressed doubts about the claims and said the remedy might encourage risky behaviour.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/country_profiles/1032156.stm#leaders \"Country profile: The Gambia\"], BBC News, 4 March 2008.</ref> In August 2007, Jammeh claimed to have developed a single dose herbal infusion that could treat [[high blood pressure]].<ref>Gambia television, 20 August 2007.</ref> Jammeh has also claimed to develop a treatment for infertility in women as part of what is called the President's Alternative Treatment Program (PATP).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panapress.com/Gambian-leader-continues-%E2%80%98fertility-treatment---13-797721-18-lang1-index.html|title=Gambia President Yahya Jammeh Continues 'Fertility Treatment'|date=1 October 2011|publisher=[[PanaPress]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story.asp?storyid=%7Be4d7e413-c6e3-47ad-a3d9-1c24fb6626ef%7D More Barren Women Seek President Jammeh's Treatment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033733/http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story.asp?storyid=%7Be4d7e413-c6e3-47ad-a3d9-1c24fb6626ef%7D |date=3 April 2012 }}, ''All Africa Global Media'', 2 October 2011.</ref><ref>Fadera, H., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201110171842.html President Jammeh Discharges Ninth Batch of Infertility Patients], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul) \u2013 All Africa Global Media'', 17 October 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\n\n==== Senegal ====\nAugust and October 2005 saw a border feud with Senegal over increased ferry prices for crossings over the [[Gambia River]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4363822.stm|title=Bid to solve Senegal-Gambia feud|last=|first=|date=21 October 2005|work=BBC News|access-date=16 March 2017}}</ref> Jammeh has a close relationship with [[Jola people|Jolas]] in the [[Casamance]] region of [[Senegal]], who allowed him to \"rule with impunity\". In turn, Jammeh supported the rebels in the [[Casamance conflict]], by engaging in the trade of illegal drugs, small arms, and also money-laundering with the rebel groups.<ref name=\":52\"/>\n\n==== Mediation and peacekeeping role ====\nShortly after the outbreak of the [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War]] in June 1998, Jammeh sought a peaceful resolution to the conflict. He personally canvassed regional opinion on the war in [[Cape Verde]], [[Mauritania]], [[Guinea]] and Senegal, and sent [[Momodou Lamin Sedat Jobe]], his foreign minister, to meet with rebel leader [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]] to fruitlessly attempt to arrange peace talks in Banjul.\n\nAccording to ''The Daily Observer'', on 10 December 2012, Jammeh secured the release of Senegalese soldiers who had been held as hostages by rebels in [[Senegal]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212101170.html \"Gambia Secures Release of Eight Senegalese Soldiers From MFDC\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 10 December 2012</ref> He sent a delegation to meet with Senegalese President [[Macky Sall]] in early December 2012. The delegation's goal was to discuss a resolution to the ongoing civil unrest in Senegal's southern region of Cassamance.<ref name=\"ReferenceA2\">\"Gambia to Discuss with Senegal Over Cassamance Conflict,\" Xinhua, 10 December 2012</ref> Members of the delegation included the Minister of Presidential Affairs, the US Ambassador to the Gambia, and members from the Red Cross and Red Crescent.<ref name=\"ReferenceA2\" />\n\nThe [[Jammeh Foundation for Peace]] (JFP) was created by Jammeh to help eradicate poverty among Gambians, improve agricultural production, and sponsor educational opportunities for needy students. The foundation has a hospital that is sponsored by the president and provides medical services to the general public.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212071282.html \"Gambia;  All Set for JFP Dinner\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 7 December 2012</ref>\n\nDonations in 2012 included $2,563,138 to the National Youths Conference and Festival (NAYCONF),<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212060982.html \"Gambia; NAYCONF Gets D2.5 Million Presidential Contribution\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 6 December 2012</ref> and \"two truckloads of turkey\" to the Gambia Christian Council for delivery to the Christian community. Jammeh also bankrolled the university of education for less privileged Gambians and non-Gambians alike both home and abroad.<ref>[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-largesse-to-christian-community \"Gambia; President Jammeh Largesse to Christian Community\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213021717/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-largesse-to-christian-community |date=13 February 2013 }}, ''The Daily Observer'', 24 December 2012</ref>\n\n==== China and Taiwan ====\n{{See also|The Gambia\u2013Taiwan relations}}\nTaiwan was formerly the \"financial lifeline\" for the regime, as part of its campaign for international support at the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\":62\"/> However, Jammeh cut ties with Taiwan during his presidency, despite then President [[Ma Ying-jeou]] having visited Gambia.\n\n=== Human rights abuses ===\n\n=== Killing of West Africa  Migrants ===\nHuman Rights Watch found that the Gambian security services most frequently implicated in abuses were the National Intelligence Agency (NIA), the paramilitary \u201cJungulers,\u201d and the Serious Crimes Unit and the Police Intervention Unit of the Gambian Police Force. The Jungulers, an unofficial unit of up to 40 personnel largely drawn from the Presidential Guard, was most frequently implicated in serious abuses, carrying out the most egregious crimes,notable among them was ordering the killing  of about 50 west Africa migrants in 2005 The victims included 44 Ghanaians, 10 Nigerians, two Senegalese, three Ivoirians and one Togolese,and were killed because the security forces feared they were mercenaries coming to try to oust Jammeh.\n\n==== Shooting of students ====\n{{See also|April 2000 Gambian student massacre}}\nOn 10 and 11 April 2000, the government was accused of the [[April 2000 Gambian student massacre|killing of 14 students and a journalist during a student demonstration]] to protest the death of a student in The Gambia. Jammeh was accused of ordering the shooting of the students, but the government denied the allegations. A government commission of inquiry reportedly concluded that the Police Intervention Unit (PIU) officers were \"largely responsible\" for many of the deaths and other injuries.<ref name=\"auto1\">[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2000/af/799.htm Country Reports on Human Rights Practices: The Gambia], U.S. Dept. of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor, 23 February 2001.</ref> The commission also said that five soldiers of the 2nd Infantry Battalion were responsible for the deaths of two students at [[Brikama]]. The government stated that the report implicated several PIU officers in the students' deaths and injuries, but those responsible were not prosecuted.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n==== Disappearances and imprisonments ====\nNewspaper reports list dozens of individuals who have disappeared after being picked up by men in plain-clothes, and others who have languished under indefinite detention for months or years without charge or trial.<ref>Ceesay, F. B., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201007060235.html Disappearance Without Trace or Detention Without Trial], ''FOROYAA Newspaper'' (Serrekunda), 5 July 2010.</ref> The regional [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) court ordered the Gambia government to produce one journalist who had disappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloggernews.net/116083|title=ECOWAS Court Orders Gambian Gov't To Produce Missing Journalist \u2013 Blogger News Network|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amnesty.org.uk/actions_details.asp?ActionID=535 AIUK: Search actions: Gambia: Release journalist Ebrima B. Manneh<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-urged-to-comply-with-ecowas-court-verdict-2010050348704.html]{{Dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> In April 2016, at least 50 people were arrested during a demonstration, and there were fears that Solo Sandeng, an opposition politician, died alongside two others while being held in detention. In July 2016, a Gambian opposition leader and another 18 people were sentenced to three years in jail for participation in the April demonstration. A Gambian diplomat publicly denied that Solo Sandeng had died in custody.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n==== Witch hunting campaign ====\nIn March 2009 [[Amnesty International]] reported that up to 1,000 Gambians had been abducted by government-sponsored \"witch doctors\" on charges of witchcraft, and taken to government detention centres where they were forced to drink poisonous hallucinogenic substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/press-releases/2009/03/gambia-hundreds-accused-e2809cwitchcrafte2809d-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20/|title=The Gambia: Hundreds accused of \"witchcraft\" and poisoned in government campaign|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/for-media/press-releases/gambia-hundreds-accused-%E2%80%9Cwitchcraft%E2%80%9D-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20|title=The Gambia: Hundreds accused of \"witchcraft\" and poisoned in government campaign|date=18 March 2009|accessdate=4 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223175800/http://www.amnesty.org/en/for-media/press-releases/gambia-hundreds-accused-%E2%80%9Cwitchcraft%E2%80%9D-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20|archivedate=23 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 21 May 2009, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the alleged witch-hunting campaign had been sparked by the President Yahya Jammeh, who believed that the death of his aunt earlier that year could be attributed to witchcraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/21/world/africa/21gambia.html|title=Witch Hunts and Foul Potions Heighten Fear of Leader in Gambia|date=21 May 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 election, crisis and ECOWAS intervention ===\n{{See also|2016\u20132017 Gambian constitutional crisis|ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia}}\nAhead of the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]] a number of opposition members, including United Democratic Party leader [[Ousainou Darboe]], were sentenced to three years in jail for staging pro-democracy protests. In a public address, Jammeh called members of the opposition \"opportunistic people supported by the West,\" adding that \"I will bow to only Allah and my mother. I will never tolerate opposition to destabilize this country.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">\"[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/gambia-jails-opposition-leader-18-other-protesters-demanding-electoral-changes-1571752 Gambia jails opposition leader and 18 other protesters for demanding electoral changes]\", ''International Business Times'', 21 July 2016</ref> The election itself took place on 1 December 2016 and, in a surprise result, Jammeh was defeated by [[Adama Barrow]] leading a coalition of opposition parties.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-38186751 |title=Gambia's Adama Barrow says shock win heralds 'new hope' |date=2 December 2016 |publisher=BBC |access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref> At first, Jammeh stated that he would not contest the result.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambia-leaders-hold-power-ends-surprising-speed-121718116.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204133106/https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambia-leaders-hold-power-ends-surprising-speed-121718116.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 December 2016 |title=Gambia leader's hold on power ends with surprising speed |last=Robbie |first=Corey-Boulet |date=3 December 2016 |agency=Associated Press |last2=John |first2=Abdoulie |access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Jammeh initially conceded defeat, on 9 December 2016 he rejected the result citing \"unacceptable abnormalities\".<ref name=\"unacceptable\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38271480|title=Gambia leader Yahya Jammeh rejects election result|date=9 December 2016|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=9 December 2016}}</ref> He subsequently announced that he had annulled the result, pending a new vote.<ref>{{Citation|title=Gambia's president 'annuls' election he lost|date=10 December 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38274631|language=en-GB|accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref> He then filed a petition with the Supreme Court of The Gambia to contest the result.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38283132|title=Gambia leader Yahya Jammeh to contest election defeat in court|date=11 December 2016|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref> The court began hearing the case on 21 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/gambia-breaking-news-supreme-court-begins-hearing-jammehs-election-petition/|title=Gambia: Breaking News: Supreme Court Begins Hearing Jammeh's Election Petition|date=21 December 2016|newspaper=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> [[ECOWAS]] warned on 23 December that it would militarily intervene to uphold the results of the election if Jammeh didn't resign by 19 January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/gambia-election-yahya-jammeh-west-african-bloc-ecowas-senegal-invasion-military-a7492966.html|title=West African bloc threatens to invade Gambia if incumbent Jammeh refuses to give up power|date=23 December 2016|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> Jammeh appointed six new judges to the Supreme Court, having sacked all but one in 2015. The hearing was to be heard on 10 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambias-top-court-adjourns-election-case-until-jan-215615280.html|title=Defiant Gambia president lets the clock run|access-date=1 January 2017}}</ref> but was delayed until May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimatefmonline.com/2017/01/12/gambias-president-jammeh-vows-stay-till-election-ruling/|title=Gambia's President Jammeh vows 'to stay till election ruling'|last=Osei|first=Leticia|date=12 January 2017|website=Ultimate FM|access-date=16 January 2017}}</ref> Jammeh stated that he would only relinquish the presidency if the court upheld the election result.\n\n[[File:Gambia President Yahya Jammeh.jpg|thumb|Yahya Jammeh.]]\nThe [[African Union]] additionally stated that it would stop recognising Jammeh as president as of 19 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=African Union says it will stop recognising Jammeh as Gambian president from January 19|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gambia-politics-afru-idUSKBN14X1RC?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews|accessdate=13 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=13 January 2017}}</ref> He attempted to have Barrow's inauguration blocked, but the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court refused to rule on the matter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38641070|title=Gambia President-elect Adama Barrow's son killed by dog|date=16 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=16 January 2017}}</ref> On Tuesday 17 January, he declared a 90-day [[state of emergency]], prohibiting \"acts of disobedience\" and \"acts intended to disturb public order\". Various ministers resigned, and about 46,000 civilians (about 75% of whom were children) fled the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38652939|title=State of emergency declared in The Gambia|date=17 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gambian President Jammeh declares state of emergency|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15119P|agency=Reuters|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UNHCR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/news/briefing/2017/1/5881deb74/senegal-around-45000-fled-political-uncertainty-gambia.html |title=Senegal: Around 45,000 have fled political uncertainty in The Gambia |first=Babar |last=Baloch |publisher=[[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] |date=20 January 2017 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> [[Senegal]], which was selected by ECOWAS to lead the operation to remove Jammeh from his post, moved its troops closer to the border with The Gambia on 18 January. Jammeh was warned to step down by midnight.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal troops move to Gambia border as Jammeh faces ultimatum|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38669347|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=18 January 2017}}</ref> Jammeh refused to step down and the deadline passed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal troops move to Gambia border as Jammeh faces ultimatum|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/38672840|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 January 2017|date=19 January 2017}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref> On 18 January, parliament voted to extend Jammeh's term by three months,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKBN1521MH|title=Gambia's parliament extends defeated president's office by 3 months \u2013 Top News |agency=Reuters|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> while in parallel, [[Adama Barrow]] was internationally recognised as President.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-38675741|title=Gambia crisis: Barrow sworn in <!-- not a mistake -->in Senegal as Jammeh stays put|date=19 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> On 19 January, Senegalese troops entered The Gambia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38682184 |title=Gambia crisis: Senegal sends in troops to back elected leader |accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> The [[United Nations Security Council]] approved a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2337|resolution]] backing Barrow while calling on Jammeh to step down. It backed ECOWAS' efforts to ensure that the results of the 2016 presidential election were respected by using political means first.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/un-adopts-resolution-backing-gambias-new-president-barrow/2017/01/19/df6a7166-de76-11e6-8902-610fe486791c_story.html |title=UN adopts resolution backing Gambia's new President Barrow |work=The Washington Post |date=19 January 2017 |accessdate=19 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119225520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/un-adopts-resolution-backing-gambias-new-president-barrow/2017/01/19/df6a7166-de76-11e6-8902-610fe486791c_story.html |archivedate=19 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Senegal halted its offensive, to allow mediation of the crisis one final time, with the invasion to proceed at noon on 20 January if Jammeh were to refuse to relinquish power.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/west-african-military-halt-gambia-operation--issue-jammeh-deadline/42861726|title=West African military halt Gambia operation, issue Jammeh deadline|agency=Reuters|publisher=Swissinfo|date=19 January 2017|access-date=19 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120024924/http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/west-african-military-halt-gambia-operation--issue-jammeh-deadline/42861726|archive-date=20 January 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jammeh again refused to step down and missed two deadlines on 20 January while regional leaders tried to persuade him to step down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/20/gambia-yahya-jammeh-midday-deadline-troops|title=The Gambia: Jammeh ignores two more deadlines to quit|work=The Guardian|date=20 January 2017|author=Ruth Maclean|access-date=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early hours of 21 January, Jammeh announced on state television that he was stepping down from the post of President,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Yahya Jammeh confirms he will step down|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/gambia-yahya-jammeh-agrees-step-170120184330091.html|accessdate=20 January 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Jammeh, facing military pressure, says steps down|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15505N?il=0|accessdate=21 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref> and left the country later on the same day, travelling to [[Guinea]] and then [[Equatorial Guinea]].<ref name=\"ReutersFlies\">{{cite news |first1=Tim |last1=Cocks |first2=Lamin |last2=Jahateh |title=Gambia's former leader Jammeh flies into exile in Equatorial Guinea |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN15505N|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=\"JammehLeavesBBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38706426 |title=Ex-President Yahya Jammeh leaves The Gambia after losing election |date=22 January 2016 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n=== Sexual Abuse and Rape Allegations ===\n\nThree women from Gambia accused the former president, Yahya Jammeh, of raping and sexually abusing them while still in office, as per rights advocacy group [[Human Rights Watch]] and TRIAL International.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/06/26/gambia-women-accuse-ex-president-sexual-violence|title=Gambia: Women Accuse Ex-President of Sexual Violence|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> According to ex-Gambian officials, women were pressured by presidential aides regularly to visit and work for Jammeh. One of the women is a Gambian pageant winner who has accused the ex-president of raping her. The victim, Fatou \"Toufah\" Jallow said she met Jammeh when she was 18 years old after winning a beauty pageant in 2014.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/jun/26/gambian-beauty-queen-accuses-ex-president-yahya-jammeh-of-rape|title=Gambian pageant winner accuses ex-president Yahya Jammeh of rape|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{ cite_web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/9/19/gambia_truth_reconciliation_commission_atrocities|title=Meet the Beauty Queen Who Inspired Gambia's Me Too Movement After Accusing Ex-Dictator of Rape | accessdate=19 September 2019|publisher=Democracy Now!}}</ref>\n\nAs per Jallow, in the months that followed, Jammeh asked her to marry him at a dinner organized by one of his aides. Later, Fatou was invited by the former president via his aide to attend a religious ceremony at the State House. However, on her arrival the victim claims to have been taken to the president\u2019s private residence where she was injected with a needle and \u201csodomized\u201d.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-48779673|title=Gambia: Appeal after rape claim against ex-president Jammeh|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In October 2019, Jallow testified before Gambia\u2019s public \"Truth and Reconciliation Commission\" about the rape charges.<ref>{{ cite web |website=Democracy Now! |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/11/1/fatou_toufah_jallow_gambia_testimony|date=Nov 1, 2019|accessdate=Nov 2, 2019|title=\"It Was Necessary\": Gambian Beauty Queen Returns Home to Testify About Rape By Former Dictator}}</ref>\n\n== Exile ==\nAs Jammeh left Gambia on 21 January 2017, Barrow stated that a \"[[Truth, Reconciliation and Reparations Commission|truth and reconciliation commission]]\" would be appointed to investigate any possible crimes committed by Jammeh. Barrow cautioned that the commission wouldn't prosecute Jammeh, only investigate the alleged crimes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adama Barrow pledges truth commission over Yahya Jammeh|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/adama-barrow-yahya-jammeh-leaving-guinea-170121175618203.html|accessdate=22 January 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> West African leaders did not guarantee any form of immunity to Jammeh.<ref>{{cite news|title=No immunity deal agreed for Gambia's Jammeh, Senegal minister says|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN1560LF?il=0|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=22 January 2017}}</ref> The United Nations, [[African Union]] and ECOWAS declared that any country offering refuge to him or his family would not be punished and he should be free to return to the country in the future. The statement added that it would work with the government of The Gambia to make sure that assets and properties legally belonging to him or his family, cabinet members, government officials or party supporters would not be seized.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's defeated leader Yahya Jammeh goes into exile |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/22/gambias-defeated-leader-yahya-jammeh-goes-exile/|accessdate=22 January 2017|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Jammeh later left Gambia for [[Equatorial Guinea]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's former leader Jammeh flies into exile in Equatorial Guinea |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN15505N|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref> where he allegedly<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Ousted Dictator Is Living the Good Life in a Palace in Equatorial Guinea|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/04/03/gambias-ousted-dictator-is-living-the-good-life-in-a-palace-in-equatorial-guinea/|accessdate=23 September 2019|publisher=Foreign Policy}}</ref> lives in a mansion in the village of [[Mongomo]].\n\nAfter Jammeh went in exile, Adama Barrow's special adviser Mai Ahmad Fatty alleged that in late January 2017, Jammeh had stolen {{currency|11.4|USD}} million from the state's treasury and used a cargo plane to ship out his luxury vehicles during his last week in power. He added that the state's treasury was virtually empty, which was confirmed by technicians in the [[Minister of Finance and Economic Affairs (Gambia)|Ministry of Finance]] as well as the [[Central Bank of the Gambia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/23/exiled-former-president-yahya-jammeh-stole-gambia|title=Exiled former president Yahya Jammeh 'stole $11.4m' from the Gambia|date=23 January 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=25 February 2017|author=Jason Burke}}</ref> About a month later, two senior ministers alleged that he had siphoned at least $50 million from social security, ports, and the national telecoms company. They also alleged that his private jet, which cost $4.5 million, was bought using the state's pension fund. The government stated that his actions had left the country with a debt of more than $1 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/23/the-gambia-debt-theft-mismanagement-jammeh-allegations|title=New claims over scale of ex-Gambian leader's theft from state coffers|date=23 February 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=25 February 2017|author=Ruth Maclean, Saikou Jammeh}}</ref> [[Reuters]] released a report regarding Jammeh's charity on 24 February 2017 in which it stated that funds from the Jammeh Foundation for Peace went to Jammeh himself, not to the foundation's projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-jammeh-idUSKBN16312M|title=Exclusive: How money flowed to Gambia's ex president|date=24 February 2017|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> The Minister of Justice announced on 10 March that the government would launch an investigation into his finances including his personal use of a charity bank account.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/gambia-probe-jammehs-finances/|title=Gambia to probe Jammeh's finances|date=10 March 2017|publisher=The Nation|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA Gambian court [[asset freezing|froze]] Jammeh's known remaining assets in The Gambia in May 2017 after it emerged he had siphoned off $50 million of public money through the state-owned telecommunications company [[Gamtel]] to his own bank accounts during his presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/gambian-authorities-seize-ex-president-jammehs-bank-accounts/a-38944380 |title=Gambian authorities seize ex-president Jammeh's bank accounts}}</ref>\n\nEffective December 21, 2017, US President [[Donald Trump]] issued an executive order under the [[Magnitsky Act]] that specifically named Yahya Jammeh among the persons whose US-based assets are to be blocked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/executive-order-blocking-property-persons-involved-serious-human-rights-abuse-corruption/|title=Executive Order Blocking the Property of Persons Involved in Serious Human Rights Abuse or Corruption|last=Trump|first=Donald|date=21 December 2017|website=Whitehouse.gov|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20171221.aspx|title=Issuance of Global Magnitsky Executive Order; Global Magnitsky Designations|last=|first=|date=|website=Treasury.gov|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn June 2018, the Gambian government decided to auction off his fleet of luxury cars and aircraft to raise money for health and education projects.\n\nOn 12 January 2020, Jammeh was warned not to return to Gambia without permission, as his safety couldn't be guaranteed, a government spokesman told the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51082371|title=Yahya Jammeh warned not to return to The Gambia|website=BBC|date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Yahya Jammeh with Obamas 2014.jpg|thumb|300px|Yahya and [[Zeinab Jammeh]] with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] in the [[White House]], August 2014.]]\n\n=== Marriages ===\n\nJammeh is an ethnic [[Jola people|Jola]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A shock victory for the underdog in Gambia|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21711208-old-style-african-despot-does-right-thing-and-goes-shock-victory|accessdate=9 December 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> Jammeh briefly dated Tuti Faal, of [[Mauritania]]n descent, in 1994 before marrying her. She worked for the Gambia Telecommunication Company (GAMTEL) until the coup in July 1994. They had difficulty conceiving a child, and in 1998 Jammeh sent her to [[Saudi Arabia]] for a [[Gynaecology|gynaecological]] exam, and during her time abroad, divorced her.<ref name=DO21 /> Jammeh married his second wife [[Zeinab Jammeh|Zeinab (Zineb) Suma Jammeh]], on 26 March 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yahya Jammeh Wife: Who Is Married To The Gambian President |url=http://www.morningledger.com/yahya-jammeh-wife-gambian-president/13129506 |website=Morning Ledger |accessdate=18 January 2017 |date=16 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228000046/http://www.morningledger.com/yahya-jammeh-wife-gambian-president/13129506/ |archive-date=28 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=DO21 /><ref>[https://twitter.com/ZinebJammeh/status/581186451859177472 Happy 16th wedding Anniversary to my beloved husband. May GOD The ALMIGHTY continue to bless our union for ever.], First Lady of Gambia on Twitter, 26 March 2015.</ref> They have two children as of 2007, a daughter, Mariam Jammeh, and a son, Muhammed Yahya Jammeh. The latter was born in late 2007, when his daughter was eight years old.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090621141453/http://www.statehouse.gm/babymuhamed-christening_311207.htm Christening of Baby Muhammed Yahya Jammeh], Office of the Gambian President website, 31 December 2007.</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2010, Jammeh announced his marriage to a 21-year-old (or possibly 18-year-old<ref name=FNdiv />) additional wife by the name Alima Sallah, daughter of Omar Gibril Sallah, Gambia's Ambassador to Saudi Arabia, and Zahra Sallah.<ref name=DO21>[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-marries-second-wife President Jammeh Marries Second Wife] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727171922/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-marries-second-wife |date=27 July 2011 }}, ''Daily Observer'', 4 October 2010.</ref><ref name=GNow21>[http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambian-president-takes-21-year-old-Alima-Sallah-as-second-wife.html Gambian president takes 21 year old Alima Sallah as second wife] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315181652/http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambian-president-takes-21-year-old-Alima-Sallah-as-second-wife.html |date=15 March 2012 }}, ''Gambia News'', 3 October 2010.</ref> It was announced that his new wife would officially be referred to as Lady Alima Yahya Jammeh, and would not be referred to as a \"first lady\", since Zeinab Suma Jammeh is the official \"first lady\".<ref name=GNow21 />\n\nAccording to at least one source, his marriage to Ms. Sallah was a shock to his other wife Zeinab Suma Jammeh, and the additional marriage led to strains in their relationship and even plans for their divorce.<ref name=MBai>M'Bai, P. N., [https://web.archive.org/web/20100702235302/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5364/Breaking-News-Gambia-SECOND-FIRST-LADY-ALIMA-SALLAH-ARRIVES-IN-USAMIDST-MOUNTING-TENSIONS-IN-KANILAI-/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia: Second First Lady Alima Sallah Arrives in U. S. \u2013 Amidst Mounting Tensions in Kanilai] ''Freedom Newspaper'', 28 June 2010.</ref> Zeinab Jammeh had reportedly already been living in the US separately from her husband for some time.<ref name=MBai /> Ms. Sallah reportedly also left Gambia for the US in June 2010.<ref name=MBai /> According to the same publication, he then divorced Ms. Sallah in early 2011.<ref name=FNdiv>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110430163742/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/6099/Breaking-News--Gambia--JAMMEH-DIVORCES-FIRST-LADY-ALIMA-SALLAH/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia \u2013 Jammeh Divorces First Lady Alima Sallah], ''Freedom Now Newspaper'' online, 26 April 2011.</ref><ref name=FNvisit>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110623221056/http://freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/6406/Gambia--Breaking-News-FIRST-LADY-JAMMEH-TO-VISIT-US-NEXT-WEEK/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia \u2013 First Lady Jammeh to Visit us Next Week], ''Freedom Now Newspaper'' online, 18 June 2011. HE reportedly tied the knot with a 22-year-old charming Ghanaian lady in Kumasi last weekend.\n\nMrs. Nora Jammeh, formerly called Munira Yahaya, a graduate of Sunyani Polytechnic, was engaged to the Gambian president two weeks ago in the Gambia, which was followed by the secret wedding at the Golden Tulip Hotel in Kumasi in 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n\nJammeh, [[Islam in the Gambia|like the majority of Gambians]], practices Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammehs-bbc-interview|title=\"President Jammeh's BBC interview\" (reprinted in the Daily Observer, Gambia, 13 December 2011)|accessdate=4 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104083346/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammehs-bbc-interview|archivedate=4 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2010, Jammeh stressed that people should believe in God: \"If you don't believe in God, you can never be grateful to humanity and you are even below a pig.\"<ref>Ndow, M., and Fadera, H., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201007270096.html Democracy of Exploitation Will Never Happen in This Country], ''The Daily Observer'' (Banjul), 26 July 2010.</ref> In 2011 he told the BBC, \"I will deliver to the Gambian people and if I have to rule this country for one billion years, I will, if Allah says so.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16148458|title=Gambia's Yahya Jammeh ready for 'billion-year' rule|date=12 December 2011|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 12 December 2015, Jammeh declared the Muslim-majority country to be an [[Islamic republic]], saying the move marked a break with the Gambia's colonial past. Jammeh told state TV that the proclamation was in line with Gambia's \"religious identity and values\". He added that no dress code would be imposed and citizens of other faiths would be allowed to practice freely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-35082343?post_id=844307525644381_949085868499879|title=Gambia declared Islamic republic by President Yahya Jammeh|date=12 December 2015|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n== Titles and styles ==\n\nThe official title used was His Excellency Sheikh Professor Alhaji Dr. Yahya Abdul-Aziz Awal Jemus Junkung Jammeh Naasiru Deen Babili Mansa.<ref>[http://www.un.org/en/ga/64/generaldebate/pdf/GM_en pdf]</ref> He was Commander in Chief of The Armed Forces and Chief Custodian of the Sacred Constitution of the Gambia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020106144503/http://www.statehouse.gm/president.html Republic of The Gambia State House Online: Office of the President], Republic of the Gambia government website.</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2015, a statement from the [[State House of the Gambia|State House]] stated that President Jammeh should be addressed as \"[[Excellency|His Excellency]] [[Sheikh]] Professor [[Hajji|Alhaji]] Dr. Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh Babili Mansa\".<ref>{{cite press release |date=16 June 2015 |title=PRESIDENT TO BE ADDRESSED AS HIS EXCELLENCY SHEIKH PROFESSOR ALHAJI DR. YAHYA A.J.J. JAMMEH BABILI MANSA |url=http://www.statehouse.gm/Press-releases/presi-title-addressed-with-babili-mansa-effective-17th-june_16062015.htm |location=Banjui |publisher=State House of the Gambia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619174146/http://www.statehouse.gm/Press-releases/presi-title-addressed-with-babili-mansa-effective-17th-june_16062015.htm |archivedate=19 June 2015 |access-date=19 June 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The title ''Babili Mansa'', which the President decided to drop in December 2014, is a phrase in the [[Mandinka language]] that could be translated as either \"Chief Bridge Builder\" or \"Conqueror of Rivers\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-33180471 |title=Gambia's President Jammeh gets extra title of 'bridge builder' |date=18 June 2015 |website= |publisher=BBC News |access-date=19 June 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.starafrica.com/news/gambia-president-jammeh-ditches-babili-mansa-title.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619195158/http://en.starafrica.com/news/gambia-president-jammeh-ditches-babili-mansa-title.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 June 2015 |title=Gambia: President Jammeh ditches Babili Mansa title |publisher= StarAfrica|access-date=19 June 2015  }}</ref> Two months before, he had already removed the title ''Nasirul Deen'' (\"Defender of the Faith\"), which had been conferred to him by the [[Gambia Supreme Islamic Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/jammeh-retakes-babili-mansa-title|title= Jammeh retakes 'Babili Mansa' title|date=17 June 2015 |work=The Point |access-date= 19 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nJammeh has received honorary doctorates from [[Saint Mary's University (Halifax)|Saint Mary's University]] of Halifax in 1999 for providing his citizens \"freedom to pursue their well-being, and to live in peace and harmony\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smu.ca/newsreleases/1999/gambiacit.html|title=Citation for President Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh on the Occasion of Presenting Him for the Degree of Doctor of Civil Law (Honoris Causa)|date=16 February 1999|publisher=Saint Mary's University|access-date=22 January 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130115124407/http://www.smu.ca/newsreleases/1999/gambiacit.html|archive-date=15 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[St. Mary's College of Maryland]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smcm.edu/news/2015/06/message-from-the-president-st-marys-colleges-peace-program/|title=Message from the President: St. Mary's College's PEACE Program \u2013 SMCM Newsroom|date=24 June 2015|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201207060986.html|title=Gambia: St Mary's College Students Observe U.S. Independence Day|first=Sheriff|last=Janko|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=26 November 2016|via=AllAfrica}}</ref> [[Universidad Empresarial de Costa Rica]], Norman Academy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grts.gm/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:grts-radio-news-may-23-2012&catid=39:news&Itemid=75|title=GRTS Radio News May 23, 2012|author=Buba Bojang|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> and [[National Taipei University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statehouse.gm/Taiwan-state-visit-itinerary_26062012.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123111117/http://www.statehouse.gm/Taiwan-state-visit-itinerary_26062012.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2013|title=Office of The Gambian President: State House Online: Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe has also received dubious awards through the [[International Parliament for Safety and Peace]], an [[List of unrecognized higher education accreditation organizations|unrecognised higher education accreditation organisation]]. Among these was a [[Nebraska Admiral]] certificate; however, Rae Hein, a spokeswoman for the [[List of governors of Nebraska|Governor of Nebraska]], stated \"We regret that this individual has attempted to embellish a certificate for a Nebraska admiralship, claiming that it was a high honour bestowed upon him by the governor, when to the best of our knowledge, this person has no relationship with or ties to Nebraska.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpj.org/security/2010/09/jammeh-award-coverage-reflects-chill-over-gambian.php|title=Jammeh 'award' coverage reflects chill in Gambian press \u2013 Committee to Protect Journalists|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201009271763.html |title=Gambia: Jammeh 'Award' Coverage Reflects Chill in Press |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first = Ishaan | last = Tharoor | url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2010/10/01/when-was-the-gambian-president-the-admiral-of-nebraska/ | title = When Was the Gambian President the Admiral of Nebraska? | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=2010-10-01 | accessdate = 2014-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5606/Breaking-News-Gambia-Governors-Office-Confirms-Authenticity-Of-Naval-Award-Extended-To-Jammeh/Default.aspx |title=Governor's Office Confirms Authenticity Of Naval Award |author=Pa Nderry M\u2019Bai |publisher=Freedom Newspaper Online (Freedomnewspaper.com) |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205254/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5606/Breaking-News-Gambia-Governors-Office-Confirms-Authenticity-Of-Naval-Award-Extended-To-Jammeh/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5644/Breaking-News-Gambia-THE-MAN-BEHIND-JAMMEHS-NEBRASKA--ADMIRAL-ADWARD-SPEAKS/Default.aspx |title=The Man Behind Jammeh's Nebraska Admiral Award Speaks |author=Pa Nderry M\u2019Bai |publisher=Freedom Newspaper Online (Freedomnewspaper.com) |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205306/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5644/Breaking-News-Gambia-THE-MAN-BEHIND-JAMMEHS-NEBRASKA--ADMIRAL-ADWARD-SPEAKS/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=freedom>{{cite news|title=Remove Yaya Jammeh from office|first=Ansu|last=Koroma|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5623/Gambia--Remove-Yaya-Jammeh-from-officeWrites-Ansu-Koroma/Default.aspx|date=2010-09-25|accessdate=2011-03-02|quote=It came to light that this award was initiated by Yaya Jammeh and brought to fruition by two individuals who claim to represent an Italian-based organization called International Parliament for Safety and Peace \u2013 an organization, according to a [[Committee to Protect Journalists|CPJ]] release, has been accused in the past for providing credentials to educational institutions otherwise not accredited in their own nations, and of selling membership, titles and other distinctions for fees. It stands to reason that Yaya Jammeh must have paid a fee to these characters, one of whom carries the title of Ambassador. [...] The second impeachable offense that Yaya Jammeh has committed is during the same award ceremony, involving the same characters who claim to be representing the International Parliament for Safety and Peace, is the claim that two awards he received were accompanied by a letter from 'President [[Barack Obama|Barrak Obama]] [sic] commending the Gambian leader for the accolade, and also commended him for helping address the most pressing needs in his community'.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224094813/http://freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5623/Gambia--Remove-Yaya-Jammeh-from-officeWrites-Ansu-Koroma/Default.aspx|archivedate=24 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=omaha>{{cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20101002/NEWS01/710029839|accessdate=2011-03-02|title=Nebraska Navy has 'unsavory despot'|quote=Last month, the certificate was delivered to Jammeh by a representative of the International Parliament for Safety and Peace, an Italian organization that has drawn criticism for recognizing diploma mills. The group also passed along two other \u201cawards\u201d to Jammeh, purportedly from President Barack Obama. A U.S. State Department official said Friday that the White House had no connection with those awards. Jammeh's honors were publicized in the Gambian press and soon drew attention from outside groups. The Committee to Protect Journalists initially was concerned that Obama and others were giving awards to Jammeh but later concluded that no honors were intended. The admiralship isn't Jammeh's first state award: Kentucky's governor made him an honorary \u201cKentucky colonel\u201d in 2008.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130182846/http://www.omaha.com/article/20101002/NEWS01/710029839|archivedate=30 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=bags>{{cite news|title=Gambia: President Jammeh Bags Four Awards|date=2010-09-17|quote=The Gambian leader, His Excellency Sheikh Professor Alhaji Dr Yahya Jammeh was Thursday presented with four different prestigious awards from the International Parliament for Safety and Peace (IPSP) upon its various initiatives in the United States of America and the Federal Republic of Germany, during a presentation ceremony held at State House in Banjul. [...] The awards include the 'President's Volunteer Call to Service Award', and the 'Platinum Award 2009 by President Barack Obama'. The last two awards are the 'Admiral of the Great Navy of the State of Nebraska', USA', given to the Gambian leader by its Governor, Dave Heinemana, whilst the fourth award, the 'Honorary Vocational Bachelors Degree' was given by the Printers and Publishers Guild of Northern Germany.}}</ref> IPSP representatives also gave Jammeh two awards and a letter from [[Barack Obama]]<ref name=bags/><ref name=Epoch>{{cite news|title=\u300a\u5916\u4ea4\u653f\u7b56\u300b\ufe55\u4eba\u6743\u8df5\u8e0f\u8005\u7684\"\u548c\u5e73\u5956\"|url=http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/10/12/13/n3112016.htm|work=[[Epoch Times]]|date=2010-12-13|accessdate=2010-12-15|trans-title=\"Foreign Policy\": human rights abuses by the \"Peace Prize\"| quote=\u5188\u6bd4\u4e9a\u603b\u7edf\u53f6\u6d77\u4e9a\u2027\u8d3e\u6885\uff08Yahya Jammeh\uff09\u4eca\u5e74\u65e9\u4e9b\u65f6\u5019\u58f0\u79f0\u6536\u5230\u4e86\u4f17\u591a\u5956\u9879\uff0c\u6ca1\u6709\u592a\u591a\u7684\u8c03\u67e5\uff0c\u751a\u81f3\u4e0d\u7528\u5f88\u591a\u8c37\u6b4c\u641c\u7d22\uff0c\u5c31\u80fd\u786e\u5b9a\u5b83\u7684\u771f\u5b9e\u6027\u4e0e\u5426\u3002\u9996\u5148\u9881\u5956\u673a\u6784\u662f\u4e0d\u660e\u4e0d\u767d\u7684\u201c\u56fd\u9645\u5b89\u5168\u4e0e\u548c\u5e73\u8bae\u4f1a\u201d(International Parliament for Safety and Peace)\uff0c\u5176\u6b21\u662f\u7535\u5b50\u5783\u573e\u90ae\u4ef6\u822c\u7684\u5f97\u5956\u540d\u5934\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\u5305\u62ec\u201c\u5fd7\u613f\u670d\u52a1\u603b\u7edf\u5956\u201d\u3001\u201c\u5df4\u62c9\u514b\u2027\u5965\u5df4\u9a6c\u603b\u7edf2009\u767d\u91d1\u5956\u201d\uff0c\u8fd8\u6709\u4ee4\u4eba\u8d28\u7591\u7684\u201c\u8363\u8a89\u804c\u4e1a\u5b66\u58eb\u5b66\u4f4d\u201d\uff0c\u7531\u5fb7\u56fd\u5317\u90e8\u7684\u51fa\u7248\u5546\u534f\u4f1a(Printers and Publishers Guild)\u9881\u53d1\u7684\u3002}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721031822/http://www.gov.gm/egov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=182%3Apres-awards&catid=14%3Anews&Itemid=1 ]</ref> that were later described as inauthentic or non-existent.<ref name=freedom/><ref name=omaha/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5622/Breaking-News-Gambia--Obama-Govt-Says-Daily-Observer-Award-Story-Is-False/Default.aspx |title=Welcome to Freedom Newspaper Online |publisher=Freedomnewspaper.com |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205344/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5622/Breaking-News-Gambia--Obama-Govt-Says-Daily-Observer-Award-Story-Is-False/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/36643 |title=afrol News \u2013 Gambia Dictator \"lied about Obama award\" |publisher=Afrol.com |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nhpr.org/gambian-leader-claims-fictitious-awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808201114/http://www.nhpr.org/gambian-leader-claims-fictitious-awards |title= Gambian Leader Claims Fictitious Awards |archivedate= 8 August 2011 |accessdate= 24 June 2017 |via= archive.org |first=J.J. |last= Sutherland |date= 29 September 2010}}</ref> Jammeh also received \"[[Russia]]n\" and \"[[Germany|German]]\" honorary degrees from members of the IPSP.<ref name=bags/><ref name=Epoch/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://allafrica.com/stories/201007060551.html |title=Gambia: Russian University Awards Doctorate Degree to President Jammeh |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Depiction on Gambian currency==\nYahya Jammeh's portrait is depicted on some of the [[Gambian dalasi]] banknotes; 2014 [[polymer]] 20 Dalasis [[banknote]] commemorating 20 Years of his regime. The N.D. (2015) issue banknotes - 5 Dalasis up to 200 Dalasis.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last=Hughes |first=Arnold |year=2000 |title='Democratisation' under the military in The Gambia: 1994\u20132000 |journal=Commonwealth & Comparative Politics |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=35\u201352 |doi=10.1080/14662040008447825 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Perfect |first=David |year=2010 |title=The Gambia under Yahya Jammeh: An Assessment |journal=The Round Table: The Commonwealth Journal of International Affairs |volume=99 |issue=406 |pages=53\u201363 |doi=10.1080/00358530903513681 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Saine |first=Abdoulaye |year=2008 |title=The Gambia's 'Elected Autocrat Poverty, Peripherality, and Political Instability,' 1994\u20132006 |journal=Armed Forces & Society |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=450\u2013473 |doi=10.1177/0095327X07312081 }}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.memritv.org/clip_transcript/en/1367.htm Jammeh to Hizbullah TV: We Support Iran's Nuclear Program; All Countries Are Entitled to Obtain Nuclear Weapons Until These Are Abolished]\n* {{Official website|www.statehouse.gm/president.html}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dawda Jawara]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Gambia]]|years=1994\u20132017<br />{{small|Acting: 1994\u20131996}}}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Adama Barrow]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{GambianPresidents}}\n{{Portal bar|The Gambia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jammeh, Yahya}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 Gambian constitutional crisis]]\n[[Category:Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction politicians]]\n[[Category:Gambian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Gambian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Leaders who took power by coup]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Gambia]]\n[[Category:People from West Coast Division (Gambia)]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Magnitsky Act]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2nd President of the Gambia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Yahya Jammeh\n|image         = Yahya Jammeh.jpg\n|office        = [[List of heads of state of the Gambia|2nd]] [[President of the Gambia]]\n|vicepresident = [[Isatou Njie-Saidy]]\n|term_start    = 6 November 1996\n|term_end      = 19 January 2017{{efn|Jammeh's term was originally scheduled to end on 19 January 2017, however, the Parliament extended his presidential term for three months, and he refused to relinquish power until 21 January when he was forced to step down after a [[ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia|regional military intervention]]. Adama Barrow nevertheless took his oath at The Gambian Embassy in Senegal on January 19th.}}\n|predecessor   = [[Dawda Jawara]]\n|successor     = [[Adama Barrow]]\n|office1        = [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council|Chairman of the Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]]\n|deputy1 = F. D. Sabali\n|term_start1    = 22 July 1994\n|term_end1      = 6 November 1996\n|predecessor1   = ''Position established''\n|successor1     = ''Position abolished''\n|birth_name    = Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jammeh\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=y|1965|5|25}}\n|birth_place   = [[Kanilai]], [[The Gambia (1965-1970)|Gambia]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Tuti Faal|1994|1998|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|[[Zeinab Jammeh|Zeinab Soumah]]|1999}}<br />{{marriage|Alima Sallah|2010|2011|reason=div}}\n|children      = 2\n|allegiance    = {{flag|The Gambia}}\n|branch        = National Gendarmerie<br />National Army\n|serviceyears  = 1984\u20131996\n|rank          = [[Colonel]]\n|commands      = National Gendarmerie\n}}\n'''Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jemus Junkung Jammeh''' (born 25 May 1965) is a Gambian politician and former military officer who was the leader of [[The Gambia]] from 1994 to 2017, firstly as chairman of the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]] (AFPRC) from 1994 to 1996 and then as [[President of the Gambia]] from 1996 to 2017.\n\nJammeh was born in [[Kanilai]], and is a [[Muslim]] of the [[Jola people|Jola ethnic group]]. He attended Gambia High School in [[Banjul]] from 1978 to 1983 and served in the [[Gambia Armed Forces|Gambia National Gendarmerie]] from 1984 to 1989. He was then commissioned as an officer of the [[Military of the Gambia|Gambia National Army]], commanding the Military Police from 1992 to 1994. In July 1994, he led a bloodless [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'etat]] that overthrew the government of [[Dawda Jawara]] and installed himself as chairman of AFPRC, a military junta, and ruled by decree until his [[1996 Gambian presidential election|election]] as president in 1996.\n\nJammeh was re-elected as president [[2001 Gambian presidential election|in 2001]], [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006]] and [[2011 Gambian presidential election|2011]], but lost to [[Adama Barrow]] [[2016 Gambian presidential election|in 2016]]. His time in office saw the authoritarian oppression of anti-government journalists, [[LGBT rights in the Gambia|LGBT people]] and opposition parties. His foreign policy led to a constantly strained relationship with the sole neighbouring country of [[Senegal]]. In 2013, Jammeh withdrew the Gambia from the [[Commonwealth of Nations]], and in 2016 he began the process of withdrawing it from the [[International Criminal Court]] (later rescinded by the Barrow government).\n\nJammeh is accused of having stolen millions of dollars from the country's coffers to fund a life of luxury. After leaving office, his assets were frozen by many countries and he went into exile. In addition to charges of corruption and human rights violations, he is also accused of having raped a number of young women.\n\n== Early life and military service ==\n\nJammeh was born on 25 May 1965 in [[Kanilai]], a village in the [[Foni Kansala]] district of the [[West Coast Division (Gambia)|Western Division]] of The Gambia. He is the son of Aja Fatou Ashombi Bojang, a housewife and trader, and Abdul Aziz James Junkung Jammeh, a career wrestler. Jammeh's grandparents migrated to the Gambia from the [[Casamance]] region of [[Senegal]].<ref>M'Bai, p. 90</ref> He had a rural upbringing as part of a [[Muslim]] [[Jola people|Jola]] family, primarily focused in Kanilai. One of his closest childhood friends was reportedly Mustapha James Kujabi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/the-gambian-dictator-who-kills-his-own-family-members-to-stay-in-power/|title=The Gambian Dictator Who Kills His Own Family Members To Stay In Power|last=|first=|date=4 September 2015|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref> He attended Kanilai primary school, Saint Edwards primary school in [[Bwiam]], from 1972 to 1978. Due to his result in the common entrance (CE) exam, he was awarded a government scholarship to [[Gambia Senior Secondary School|Gambia High School]] in [[Banjul]], in 1978. His formal education ended after he received his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O Levels]] in 1983.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/28/world/in-gambia-new-coup-follows-old-pattern.html|title=In Gambia, New Coup Follows Old Pattern|last=French|first=Howard W.|date=28 August 1994|work=The New York Times|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-takes-nomination-turn-at-iec-today|title=President Jammeh takes nomination turn at IEC today|last=|first=|date=10 November 2016|work=The Point|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Hughes and Perfect, pp. 109-111</ref>{{Quote box\n|quote = In those days, he used to defend the rights of many Gendarmes who for one reason or another had felt apart with the Gendarmerie command and administration and were brought to the [Military Police] for either investigation or punishment. What actually makes him changed into the biggest violator of the human and civic rights of ordinary Gambian citizens is beyond my comprehension|source = |width = 25%|author = Capt. Bunja Darboe (rtd)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jollofnews.com/2016/07/26/gambia-why-am-i-speaking-now/|title=Why Am I Speaking Now?|last=Darboe|first=Bunja|date=12 July 2016|work=Jollof News|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 1984, Jammeh joined what was then the Gambian National Gendarmerie as a private. He was part of the Special Intervention Unit from 1984 to 1986 and was an escort training instructor at the Gendarmerie Training School from 1986 to 1989. He was promoted to sergeant in April 1986, and to cadet officer in December 1987.<ref name=\":1\" /> A former Gendarmerie officer, Binneh S. Minteh, later claimed that Jammeh \"had always singled out Mandinka\u2019s as bad people\" during his time as a Gendarme. In particular, Minteh recalled Jammeh's \"ruthless and disrespectful encounter\" with sergeant major Kebba Dibba, and when he \"brandished a pistol and threatened to shoot\" Captain Ebrima Camara simply on the basis of their ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gainako.com/president-jammehs-threats-mandinkas-gambia-irresponsible-repugnant-national-leader/|title=President Jammeh's Threats against Mandinka's in Gambia are Irresponsible and Repugnant of a National Leader|last=Minteh|first=Binneh S.|date=16 June 2016|work=Gainako|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined the Gambia National Army and was commissioned as a second lieutenant on 29 September 1989, serving as the officer in charge (OIC) of the Presidential Escort, part of the Presidential Guards, from 1989 to 1990. In 1991, he served as the officer commanding (OC) the Mobile Gendarmerie, and from 1992 to 1994 was the OC of the Gambia National Army Military Police. On 1 February 1992, he had been promoted to lieutenant. Jammeh was the head of security detail attached to [[Pope John Paul II]] during his visit to the Gambia in February 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/the-man-who-provided-security-to-the-late-pope-john-paul-the-ii-in-february-of-1992-later-toppled-jawara-from-power/|title=The Man Who Provided Security To The Late Pope John Paul, the II, In February Of 1992, Later Toppled Jawara From Power|last=|first=|date=3 August 2015|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> He attended the [[Military Police Officers Basic Course]] (MPOBC) at [[Fort McClellan]] in the [[United States]] from September 1993 to January 1994.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== 1994 coup d'etat and military rule ==\n\n=== 1994 coup d'etat ===\nJammeh was one of the four junior Army officers who organised the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'etat]] against [[Dawda Jawara]]'s government. The other three were Sana Sabally, [[Sadibou Hydara]] and Edward Singhateh. The coup, which took place on 22 July, was successful and bloodless, leading to Jawara fleeing into exile.<ref name=\":3\">Hughes and Perfect, p. xxix</ref> Four days later, on 26 July, the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]] (AFPRC) was formed with Jammeh as its chairman.<ref name=\":2\" /> Jammeh promised that it would be a \"coup with a difference\", and that the country would be returned to civilian rule \"as soon as we have set things right\". One result of the coup was that the [[European Union]] and the United States, the major donors of foreign aid to the Gambia, suspended their aid programmes until the country was returned to civil rule. Jammeh claimed the suspension of aid programmes amounted to \"[[neocolonialism]]\". A Western diplomat who spoke to ''[[The New York Times]]'' said, \"This is exactly the same phenomenon we have seen elsewhere, with the only difference being that so far there has been no violence.\" In particular, the coup was compared with [[Samuel Doe]]'s in the [[Liberia]], which led to the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe 1994 coup d'etat in the Gambia, overthrowing the government of Dawda Jawara, represented a buck in the post-1989 sub-Saharan Africa trend away from authoritarianism and towards multiparty politics. The Gambia had represented an anomaly in Africa as one of the few countries that had a functioning democracy prior to 1989.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edie|first=Carlene, J.|year=2000|title=Democracy in the Gambia: Past, Present and Prospects for the Future|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/ad/article/viewFile/22106/19406|journal=Africa Development|volume=XXV|pages=161\u2013198|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Rule through the AFPRC ===\nIn the aftermath of the coup, Jammeh governed by decree alongside four other junior officers and several civilians. He banned all political activity, arrested two socialist journalists, and detained several of his Army superiors. He also confined ministers of Jawara's government to [[house arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On 17 October, Jammeh announced that there would be a four-year transition to civilian government. In November 1994, the same month when Jammeh was formally promoted to the rank of captain, there was an unsuccessful coup attempt by several disaffected young officers leading in numerous deaths, but Jammeh remained in power. The National Consultative Committee (NCC) was appointed on 7 December to review the transition process, and when they reported on 27 January 1995, they recommended a two-year transition period. The same day as the NCC's report, two of the original coup leaders, Sabally and Hydara, launched an unsuccessful attempt to overthrow Jammeh as chairman. Subsequently, Singhateh was appointed as vice-chairman of the AFPRC, and Hydara died in prison on 3 June.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Constitutional Review Commission (CRC) was appointed in April 1995 and reported to the government in November 1995. Its report was published in March 1996 was put to a [[1996 Gambian constitutional referendum|national referendum]] on 8 August 1996. The new constitution, which provided for multiparty elections, an unlimited number of five-year presidential terms, and a lowering of the voting age from 21 to 18, was approved by a majority of 70%. According to Saine, Jammeh would \"[enjoy] unrivalled political and economic power as a consequence of the new constitution. In contrast, opposition political parties [would be] sidelined and allowed little political space in a one-sided electoral contest in which Jammeh was the assured \u2018winner\u2019.\"<ref name=\":42\">Saine, p. 261</ref> Decree no. 89, issued on 14 August, reiterated the ban on the [[People's Progressive Party (Gambia)|PPP]], the [[National Convention Party (Gambia)|NCP]] and the [[Gambian People's Party|GPP]], but lifted the ban on the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism|PDOIS]] and the [[Gambia Party for Democracy and Progress|PDP]]. In 1996, on 28 August, Jammeh was formally promoted to the rank of colonel and then retired from the army on 6 September, one month before the 1996 presidential election.<ref name=\":3\" /> His retirement was marked by a ceremony that was described as \"actually a political event made palatable by a patina of military pomp.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/96BANJUL2256_a.html|title=Chairman Jammeh Retires From The Army - As A Colonel|last=|first=|date=13 September 1996|website=Wikileaks|access-date=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== President of the Gambia ==\n\n=== 1996 and 1997 elections ===\nJammeh won the [[1996 Gambian presidential election|1996 presidential election]] as the APRC candidate, winning 56% of the vote and beating [[Ousainou Darboe]], [[Hamat Bah]] and [[Sidia Jatta]]. Darboe was forced to seek refuge in the Senegalese embassy in Banjul, fearing an assassination plot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/WORLD/9609/28/newsbriefs/|title=Gambia army ruler wins election|last=|first=|date=28 September 1996|work=CNN|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> In the [[1997 Gambian parliamentary election|1997 parliamentary election]], the first to the new National Assembly put in place by the 1996 constitution, the APRC won a majority of seats. However, these two elections, the first following the transition from military to civil rule, were \"marred by provisions of the new, doctored constitution, an electoral commission appointed by Jammeh alone in 1995 and a political network that included the Green Boys \u2013 a now-disbanded vigilante group that was mobilised to intimidate the electorate to ensure Jammeh\u2019s \u2018victory\u2019.\" Saine argues that this combination of intimidation and harassment of the opposition, an inherent bias provided by the 1996 constitution, as well as a distinct financial advantage, meant that \"the presidential and national assembly elections were lost long before the first ballot was cast.\"<ref name=\":42\"/>\n\n=== Elections ===\nJammeh founded the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]] as his political party. He was elected as president in September 1996.<ref name=USBackground>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/5459.htm Background Note: The Gambia], U.S. Department of State, 22 April 2011.</ref> Foreign observers did not deem these elections free and fair.<ref name=USBackground /> He was re-elected on 18 October 2001 with about 53% of the vote; this election was generally deemed free and fair by observers,<ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2001/af/8377.htm Country Report on Human Rights Practices for The Gambia], U.S. Department of State, 4 March 2002.</ref> despite some very serious shortcomings ranging from overt government intimidation of voters to technical innovations (such as raising the required deposit to stand for election by a factor of 25) to distort the process in favour of the incumbent regime.<ref>\"Democratization in Africa\" by Diamond and Plattner (ed), Johns Hopkins University Press (1999), pages 216\u2013227 [https://books.google.com/books?id=olOGLS8yPREC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=&f=false]</ref>\n\nA coup attempt against Jammeh was reported to have been thwarted on 21 March 2006; Jammeh, who was in [[Mauritania]] at the time, quickly returned home. Army chief of staff Col. Ndure Cham, the alleged leader of the plot,<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=52380&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=GAMBIA \"Attempted coup averted, government says\"], IRIN, 22 March 2006.</ref> reportedly fled to neighbouring [[Senegal]], while other alleged conspirators were arrested<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4852190.stm \"Arrests over Gambia 'coup plot'\"], BBC News, 28 March 2006.</ref> and were put on trial for treason.<ref>[http://www.afrol.com/articles/21796 \"Suspected Gambian coupists before court martial\"], Afrol News, 6 October 2006.</ref> In April 2007, ten former officers accused of involvement were convicted and given prison sentences; four of them were sentenced to life in prison.<ref>[https://archive.today/20070517203204/http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=nw20070419213835762C477763 \"Gambia jails army coup plotters\"], Reuters (''IOL''), 20 April 2007.</ref>\n\nJammeh ran for a third term in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|presidential election]] held on 22 September 2006; the election was initially planned for October but was moved forward because of the Muslim holy month of [[Ramadan]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5352242.stm \"Q&A: Gambia votes\"], BBC News, 21 September 2006.</ref> He was re-elected with 67.3% of the vote and was declared the winner of the election; the opposition candidate [[Ousainou Darboe]] finished second, as in 2001.<ref name=\"winner\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5369040.stm \"Gambian president is re-elected\"], BBC News, 23 September 2006.</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Jammeh was again re-elected as president for a fourth term in office, reportedly having received 72% of the popular vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-15897134|title=Gambia president wins fourth term|date=2011-11-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic policy ===\n\n==== Suppression of the press ====\nOne of Jammeh's consistent targets throughout his time as President was the press and the media, as a whole as well as individual journalists. In 1998, the independent Citizen FM radio station was forced to close after a number of its staff were arrested and its equipment was confiscated. After its American proprietor sold it to a businessman with close ties to Jammeh in 1999, ''[[The Daily Observer]]'' became notably pro-Jammeh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2000/03/attacks-on-the-press-1999-the-gambia.php|title=Attacks on the Press 1999: The Gambia|last=|first=|date=22 March 2000|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref> In August 2000, the anti-government Radio 1 FM suffered an arson attack.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2001/03/attacks-on-the-press-2000-the-gambia.php|title=Attacks on the Press 2000: The Gambia|last=|first=|date=2001|website=Committee to Protect Journalists|access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref> [[Gambian Americans|Gambian American]] author Abdoulaye Saine states that Jammeh was able to use [[Gambia Radio & Television Service]] as his personal propaganda outlet whenever he required.<ref name=\":62\">Saine, p. 263</ref>\n\nJammeh has made a number of public statements against the press. In July 2000, he said that \"anybody bent on disturbing the peace and stability of the nation [would] be buried six feet deep.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> In April 2004, Jammeh told journalists to obey his government \"or go to hell\". In June 2005, he said that he had allowed \"too much freedom of expression\" in the Gambia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061127093825/http://www.rsf.org/IMG/pdf/Page_16_6.pdf Yahya Abdul-Aziz Jemus Junkung Jammeh], Reporters Without Borders.</ref>\n\nIn response to his suppression of the press and media in the Gambia, various online newspapers and radio stations were established by self-exiled Gambian journalists to publicise alleged government atrocities. These include ''Freedom Newspaper'', ''The Gambia Echo'' and ''Gainako''.<ref name=\":62\"/>\n\nJammeh also saw through legislation to restrict the activities of the press. The Newspaper Act 1994 imposed criminal penalties on private publications that failed to pay a yearly registration fee. The National Media Communication Act 2000 forced journalists to reveal confidential sources to police and the judiciary on demand.<ref name=\":8\" /> In December 2004, the Criminal Code (Amendment) Bill 2004 allowed prison terms for defamation and sedition. The same month, the Newspaper (Amendment) Bill 2004 required newspaper proprietors to purchase expensive operating licenses and forcing them to register their homes as [[Security (finance)|security]].\n\nA number of individual journalists were also targeted. In December 2004, [[Deyda Hydara]], then editor of [[The Point (the Gambia)|''The Point'']], announced his intention to publicly challenge newly-introduced legislation restricting press freedoms.  He was shot and killed when driving home in Banjul on 16 December, leading to thousands protesting on the streets.<ref name=\"auto3\">[http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=52505 \"Thousands protest peacefully at murder of journalist\"], IRIN, 22 December 2004.</ref> Some pointed at the government, led by Jammeh, as the murderers, but it has remained unsolved.<ref name=\"auto3\" /> Furthermore, in July 2006, [[Ebrima Manneh]] of ''The Daily Observer'' was arrested by state security after attempting to publish a [[BBC]] report critical of Jammeh. His arrest was witnessed by his coworkers,<ref name=\"CFP2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpj.org/2009/04/gambia-must-account-for-missing-journalist-ebrima.php|title=Gambia must account for missing journalist Ebrima Manneh|date=14 April 2009|publisher=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and, despite being ordered to release Manneh by an ECOWAS court, the government denied that Manneh was still imprisoned.<ref name=\"AFP2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5izABjky1HY0Bz47DUuc3V3SaNLGQ|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420053701/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5izABjky1HY0Bz47DUuc3V3SaNLGQ|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 April 2009|title=Missing Gambia journalist is dead: police|date=14 April 2009|agency=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=18 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> An unnamed police source said that he believed Manneh \"is no longer alive\".<ref name=\"AFP2\" /> Both [[Amnesty International]] and the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] have called for his release.<ref name=\"CFP2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|title=Ebrima Manneh|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|accessdate=17 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429082908/http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|archivedate=29 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Women's rights ====\nIn December 2015, Jammeh banned [[female genital mutilation]] (FGM) in The Gambia, labelling the practice of FGM as having \"no place in Islam or in modern society\"; anyone that ignored the ban would face a prison sentence of up to three years. After the end of [[Ramadan]] and [[Eid ul-Fitr]] in July 2016, Jammeh further announced a ban on [[child marriages]]. In 2016, some 30% of women were married while under the age of 18. Yahya Jammeh's response was that anyone caught marrying a girl under 18 years of age would be jailed for up to twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36746174|title=Gambia and Tanzania outlaw child marriage|date=8 July 2016|accessdate=26 November 2016|via=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==== Judiciary ====\nAs President, Jammeh had significant influence over the judiciary in the Gambia, particularly because Section 98 of the 1996 constitution permits the President to appoint judges directly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrlibrary.umn.edu/research/gambia-constitution.pdf|title=Constitution of the Republic of the Gambia|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Minnesota Human Rights Library|access-date=}}</ref> Saine argues that Jammeh's employment of mainly foreign judges allows him to effectively issue tough sentences to reduce dissent and to imprison both real and perceived threats to the president's power.<ref name=\":52\">Saine, p. 262</ref>\n\n==== LGBT rights ====\n{{See also|LGBT rights in the Gambia}}\nOn 15 May 2008, Jammeh announced that his government would introduce legislation that would set laws against homosexuals that would be \"stricter than those in [[Iran]]\", and that he would \"cut off the head\" of any gay or lesbian person discovered in the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\">[http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambia-News-President-Jammeh-Gives-Ultimatum-for-Homosexuals-to-.html President Jammeh Gives Ultimatum for Homosexuals to Leave] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315181156/http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambia-News-President-Jammeh-Gives-Ultimatum-for-Homosexuals-to-.html |date=15 March 2012 }}, Gambia News, 19 May 2008.</ref> News reports indicated his government intended to execute all homosexuals in the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\" /> In a speech given in Tallinding, Jammeh gave a \"final ultimatum\" to any gays or lesbians in the Gambia, warning them to leave the country.<ref name=\"JamehHomosexuality2\" /> In a speech to the United Nations on 27 September 2013, Jammeh said \"[h]omosexuality in all its forms and manifestations which, though very evil, antihuman as well as anti-Allah, is being promoted as a human right by some powers,\" who \"want to put an end to human existence.\"<ref name=\"JamehHomosexualityII2\">[https://news.yahoo.com/gambian-president-says-gays-threat-human-existence-20130928-122519635.html Gambian president says gays a threat to human existence-20130928], Reuters, 28 September 2013.</ref> On 18 February 2014, Jammeh called homosexuals \"vermins\" by saying that: \"We will fight these vermins [''sic''] called homosexuals or gays the same way we are fighting malaria-causing mosquitoes, if not more aggressively\". He also went on to disparage the [[LGBT]] by saying that \"As far as I am concerned, LGBT can only stand for [[Leprosy]], [[Gonorrhoea]], Bacteria and [[Tuberculosis]], all of which are detrimental to human existence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/18/us-gambia-homosexuality-idUSBREA1H1S820140218|title=Gambia's Jammeh calls gays 'vermin', says to fight like mosquitoes|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21623667-many-places-attacking-rights-gay-people-can-still-be-politically-useful-and|title=Tainting love|date=11 October 2014|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, in defiance of western criticism Jammeh intensified his anti-gay rhetoric, telling a crowd during an agricultural tour: \"If you do it [in the Gambia] I will slit your throat \u2013 if you are a man and want to marry another man in this country and we catch you, no one will ever set eyes on you again, and no white person can do anything about it.\"<ref>[https://news.vice.com/article/gambian-president-says-he-will-slit-gay-mens-throats-in-public-speech Gambian President Says He Will Slit Gay Men's Throats in Public Speech], [[Vice News]], 11 May 2015</ref>\n\nThis prompted a fresh round of condemnation from international human rights leaders. [[National Security Advisor (United States)|US National Security Advisor]] [[Susan Rice]] released a statement of condemnation on 16 May 2015: \"We condemn his comments, and note these threats come amid an alarming deterioration of the broader human rights situation in The Gambia,\" said Rice. \"We are deeply concerned about credible reports of torture, suspicious disappearances \u2013 including of two American citizens \u2013 and arbitrary detention at the government's hands.\"<ref>[http://www.washingtonblade.com/2015/05/16/susan-rice-condemns-gambia-presidents-anti-gay-comments/ U.S. slams Gambia president's anti-gay comments], ''[[Washington Blade]]'', 16 May 2015</ref>\n\n==== HIV/AIDS policy ====\nIn January 2007, Jammeh claimed he could cure [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[asthma]] with natural herbs.<ref name=\"BBCHIV\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6323449.stm \"President's 'HIV cure' condemned\"], BBC News, 2 February 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Observer41\">[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-discharges-41-hivaids-treated-patients President Jammeh discharges 41 HIV/AIDS treated patients] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727171859/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-discharges-41-hivaids-treated-patients |date=27 July 2011 }}, ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 12 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/19/gambia-witchcraft-hallucinogenics|title=Gambian state kidnaps 1,000 villagers in mass purge of 'witchcraft'|last=Rice|first=Xan|date=2009-03-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> His claimed treatment program includes instructing patients to cease taking their anti-retroviral drugs.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2007-02-20-gambia_x.htm Gambian president's claim of AIDS cure causes alarm], ''[[USA Today]]'', 20 February 2007.</ref><ref>Dibba, L. M., [http://allafrica.com/stories/200701190658.html Jammeh starts curing HIV/AIDS patients today], ''The Daily Observer'' (Banjul), 18 January 2007.</ref> His claims have been criticised for promoting unscientific treatment that could have dangerous results, including the infection of others by those who thought they had been cured by the method.<ref name=\"BBCHIV\" /><ref name=\"Observer41\" /> In December 2011, he restated during an interview that the alleged cure for HIV/AIDS was \"going very well\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16144116 \"Gambia President Yahya Jammeh: Critics 'can go to hell'\"], BBC News, 12 December 2011</ref>\n\nFadzai Gwaradzimba, the country representative of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] in the Gambia, was told to leave the country after she expressed doubts about the claims and said the remedy might encourage risky behaviour.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/country_profiles/1032156.stm#leaders \"Country profile: The Gambia\"], BBC News, 4 March 2008.</ref> In August 2007, Jammeh claimed to have developed a single dose herbal infusion that could treat [[high blood pressure]].<ref>Gambia television, 20 August 2007.</ref> Jammeh has also claimed to develop a treatment for infertility in women as part of what is called the President's Alternative Treatment Program (PATP).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panapress.com/Gambian-leader-continues-%E2%80%98fertility-treatment---13-797721-18-lang1-index.html|title=Gambia President Yahya Jammeh Continues 'Fertility Treatment'|date=1 October 2011|publisher=[[PanaPress]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story.asp?storyid=%7Be4d7e413-c6e3-47ad-a3d9-1c24fb6626ef%7D More Barren Women Seek President Jammeh's Treatment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033733/http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story.asp?storyid=%7Be4d7e413-c6e3-47ad-a3d9-1c24fb6626ef%7D |date=3 April 2012 }}, ''All Africa Global Media'', 2 October 2011.</ref><ref>Fadera, H., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201110171842.html President Jammeh Discharges Ninth Batch of Infertility Patients], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul) \u2013 All Africa Global Media'', 17 October 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\n\n==== Senegal ====\nAugust and October 2005 saw a border feud with Senegal over increased ferry prices for crossings over the [[Gambia River]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4363822.stm|title=Bid to solve Senegal-Gambia feud|last=|first=|date=21 October 2005|work=BBC News|access-date=16 March 2017}}</ref> Jammeh has a close relationship with [[Jola people|Jolas]] in the [[Casamance]] region of [[Senegal]], who allowed him to \"rule with impunity\". In turn, Jammeh supported the rebels in the [[Casamance conflict]], by engaging in the trade of illegal drugs, small arms, and also money-laundering with the rebel groups.<ref name=\":52\"/>\n\n==== Mediation and peacekeeping role ====\nShortly after the outbreak of the [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War]] in June 1998, Jammeh sought a peaceful resolution to the conflict. He personally canvassed regional opinion on the war in [[Cape Verde]], [[Mauritania]], [[Guinea]] and Senegal, and sent [[Momodou Lamin Sedat Jobe]], his foreign minister, to meet with rebel leader [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]] to fruitlessly attempt to arrange peace talks in Banjul.\n\nAccording to ''The Daily Observer'', on 10 December 2012, Jammeh secured the release of Senegalese soldiers who had been held as hostages by rebels in [[Senegal]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212101170.html \"Gambia Secures Release of Eight Senegalese Soldiers From MFDC\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 10 December 2012</ref> He sent a delegation to meet with Senegalese President [[Macky Sall]] in early December 2012. The delegation's goal was to discuss a resolution to the ongoing civil unrest in Senegal's southern region of Cassamance.<ref name=\"ReferenceA2\">\"Gambia to Discuss with Senegal Over Cassamance Conflict,\" Xinhua, 10 December 2012</ref> Members of the delegation included the Minister of Presidential Affairs, the US Ambassador to the Gambia, and members from the Red Cross and Red Crescent.<ref name=\"ReferenceA2\" />\n\nThe [[Jammeh Foundation for Peace]] (JFP) was created by Jammeh to help eradicate poverty among Gambians, improve agricultural production, and sponsor educational opportunities for needy students. The foundation has a hospital that is sponsored by the president and provides medical services to the general public.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212071282.html \"Gambia;  All Set for JFP Dinner\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 7 December 2012</ref>\n\nDonations in 2012 included $2,563,138 to the National Youths Conference and Festival (NAYCONF),<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201212060982.html \"Gambia; NAYCONF Gets D2.5 Million Presidential Contribution\"], ''The Daily Observer (Banjul)'', 6 December 2012</ref> and \"two truckloads of turkey\" to the Gambia Christian Council for delivery to the Christian community. Jammeh also bankrolled the university of education for less privileged Gambians and non-Gambians alike both home and abroad.<ref>[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-largesse-to-christian-community \"Gambia; President Jammeh Largesse to Christian Community\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213021717/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-largesse-to-christian-community |date=13 February 2013 }}, ''The Daily Observer'', 24 December 2012</ref>\n\n==== China and Taiwan ====\n{{See also|The Gambia\u2013Taiwan relations}}\nTaiwan was formerly the \"financial lifeline\" for the regime, as part of its campaign for international support at the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\":62\"/> However, Jammeh cut ties with Taiwan during his presidency, despite then President [[Ma Ying-jeou]] having visited Gambia.\n\n=== Human rights abuses ===\n\n=== Killing of West Africa  Migrants ===\nHuman Rights Watch found that the Gambian security services most frequently implicated in abuses were the National Intelligence Agency (NIA), the paramilitary \u201cJungulers,\u201d and the Serious Crimes Unit and the Police Intervention Unit of the Gambian Police Force. The Jungulers, an unofficial unit of up to 40 personnel largely drawn from the Presidential Guard, was most frequently implicated in serious abuses, carrying out the most egregious crimes,notable among them was ordering the killing  of about 50 west Africa migrants in 2005 The victims included 44 Ghanaians, 10 Nigerians, two Senegalese, three Ivoirians and one Togolese,and were killed because the security forces feared they were mercenaries coming to try to oust Jammeh.\n\n==== Shooting of students ====\n{{See also|April 2000 Gambian student massacre}}\nOn 10 and 11 April 2000, the government was accused of the [[April 2000 Gambian student massacre|killing of 14 students and a journalist during a student demonstration]] to protest the death of a student in The Gambia. Jammeh was accused of ordering the shooting of the students, but the government denied the allegations. A government commission of inquiry reportedly concluded that the Police Intervention Unit (PIU) officers were \"largely responsible\" for many of the deaths and other injuries.<ref name=\"auto1\">[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2000/af/799.htm Country Reports on Human Rights Practices: The Gambia], U.S. Dept. of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor, 23 February 2001.</ref> The commission also said that five soldiers of the 2nd Infantry Battalion were responsible for the deaths of two students at [[Brikama]]. The government stated that the report implicated several PIU officers in the students' deaths and injuries, but those responsible were not prosecuted.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n==== Disappearances and imprisonments ====\nNewspaper reports list dozens of individuals who have disappeared after being picked up by men in plain-clothes, and others who have languished under indefinite detention for months or years without charge or trial.<ref>Ceesay, F. B., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201007060235.html Disappearance Without Trace or Detention Without Trial], ''FOROYAA Newspaper'' (Serrekunda), 5 July 2010.</ref> The regional [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) court ordered the Gambia government to produce one journalist who had disappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloggernews.net/116083|title=ECOWAS Court Orders Gambian Gov't To Produce Missing Journalist \u2013 Blogger News Network|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amnesty.org.uk/actions_details.asp?ActionID=535 AIUK: Search actions: Gambia: Release journalist Ebrima B. Manneh<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-urged-to-comply-with-ecowas-court-verdict-2010050348704.html]{{Dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> In April 2016, at least 50 people were arrested during a demonstration, and there were fears that Solo Sandeng, an opposition politician, died alongside two others while being held in detention. In July 2016, a Gambian opposition leader and another 18 people were sentenced to three years in jail for participation in the April demonstration. A Gambian diplomat publicly denied that Solo Sandeng had died in custody.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n==== Witch hunting campaign ====\nIn March 2009 [[Amnesty International]] reported that up to 1,000 Gambians had been abducted by government-sponsored \"witch doctors\" on charges of witchcraft, and taken to government detention centres where they were forced to drink poisonous hallucinogenic substances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/press-releases/2009/03/gambia-hundreds-accused-e2809cwitchcrafte2809d-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20/|title=The Gambia: Hundreds accused of \"witchcraft\" and poisoned in government campaign|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/for-media/press-releases/gambia-hundreds-accused-%E2%80%9Cwitchcraft%E2%80%9D-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20|title=The Gambia: Hundreds accused of \"witchcraft\" and poisoned in government campaign|date=18 March 2009|accessdate=4 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223175800/http://www.amnesty.org/en/for-media/press-releases/gambia-hundreds-accused-%E2%80%9Cwitchcraft%E2%80%9D-and-poisoned-government-campaign-20|archivedate=23 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 21 May 2009, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the alleged witch-hunting campaign had been sparked by the President Yahya Jammeh, who believed that the death of his aunt earlier that year could be attributed to witchcraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/21/world/africa/21gambia.html|title=Witch Hunts and Foul Potions Heighten Fear of Leader in Gambia|date=21 May 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 election, crisis and ECOWAS intervention ===\n{{See also|2016\u20132017 Gambian constitutional crisis|ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia}}\nAhead of the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]] a number of opposition members, including United Democratic Party leader [[Ousainou Darboe]], were sentenced to three years in jail for staging pro-democracy protests. In a public address, Jammeh called members of the opposition \"opportunistic people supported by the West,\" adding that \"I will bow to only Allah and my mother. I will never tolerate opposition to destabilize this country.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">\"[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/gambia-jails-opposition-leader-18-other-protesters-demanding-electoral-changes-1571752 Gambia jails opposition leader and 18 other protesters for demanding electoral changes]\", ''International Business Times'', 21 July 2016</ref> The election itself took place on 1 December 2016 and, in a surprise result, Jammeh was defeated by [[Adama Barrow]] leading a coalition of opposition parties.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-38186751 |title=Gambia's Adama Barrow says shock win heralds 'new hope' |date=2 December 2016 |publisher=BBC |access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref> At first, Jammeh stated that he would not contest the result.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambia-leaders-hold-power-ends-surprising-speed-121718116.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204133106/https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambia-leaders-hold-power-ends-surprising-speed-121718116.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 December 2016 |title=Gambia leader's hold on power ends with surprising speed |last=Robbie |first=Corey-Boulet |date=3 December 2016 |agency=Associated Press |last2=John |first2=Abdoulie |access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Jammeh initially conceded defeat, on 9 December 2016 he rejected the result citing \"unacceptable abnormalities\".<ref name=\"unacceptable\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38271480|title=Gambia leader Yahya Jammeh rejects election result|date=9 December 2016|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=9 December 2016}}</ref> He subsequently announced that he had annulled the result, pending a new vote.<ref>{{Citation|title=Gambia's president 'annuls' election he lost|date=10 December 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38274631|language=en-GB|accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref> He then filed a petition with the Supreme Court of The Gambia to contest the result.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38283132|title=Gambia leader Yahya Jammeh to contest election defeat in court|date=11 December 2016|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=11 December 2016}}</ref> The court began hearing the case on 21 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/gambia-breaking-news-supreme-court-begins-hearing-jammehs-election-petition/|title=Gambia: Breaking News: Supreme Court Begins Hearing Jammeh's Election Petition|date=21 December 2016|newspaper=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> [[ECOWAS]] warned on 23 December that it would militarily intervene to uphold the results of the election if Jammeh didn't resign by 19 January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/gambia-election-yahya-jammeh-west-african-bloc-ecowas-senegal-invasion-military-a7492966.html|title=West African bloc threatens to invade Gambia if incumbent Jammeh refuses to give up power|date=23 December 2016|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> Jammeh appointed six new judges to the Supreme Court, having sacked all but one in 2015. The hearing was to be heard on 10 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/gambias-top-court-adjourns-election-case-until-jan-215615280.html|title=Defiant Gambia president lets the clock run|access-date=1 January 2017}}</ref> but was delayed until May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimatefmonline.com/2017/01/12/gambias-president-jammeh-vows-stay-till-election-ruling/|title=Gambia's President Jammeh vows 'to stay till election ruling'|last=Osei|first=Leticia|date=12 January 2017|website=Ultimate FM|access-date=16 January 2017}}</ref> Jammeh stated that he would only relinquish the presidency if the court upheld the election result.\n\n[[File:Gambia President Yahya Jammeh.jpg|thumb|Yahya Jammeh.]]\nThe [[African Union]] additionally stated that it would stop recognising Jammeh as president as of 19 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=African Union says it will stop recognising Jammeh as Gambian president from January 19|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gambia-politics-afru-idUSKBN14X1RC?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews|accessdate=13 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=13 January 2017}}</ref> He attempted to have Barrow's inauguration blocked, but the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court refused to rule on the matter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38641070|title=Gambia President-elect Adama Barrow's son killed by dog|date=16 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=16 January 2017}}</ref> On Tuesday 17 January, he declared a 90-day [[state of emergency]], prohibiting \"acts of disobedience\" and \"acts intended to disturb public order\". Various ministers resigned, and about 46,000 civilians (about 75% of whom were children) fled the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38652939|title=State of emergency declared in The Gambia|date=17 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gambian President Jammeh declares state of emergency|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15119P|agency=Reuters|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UNHCR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/news/briefing/2017/1/5881deb74/senegal-around-45000-fled-political-uncertainty-gambia.html |title=Senegal: Around 45,000 have fled political uncertainty in The Gambia |first=Babar |last=Baloch |publisher=[[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] |date=20 January 2017 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> [[Senegal]], which was selected by ECOWAS to lead the operation to remove Jammeh from his post, moved its troops closer to the border with The Gambia on 18 January. Jammeh was warned to step down by midnight.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal troops move to Gambia border as Jammeh faces ultimatum|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38669347|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=18 January 2017}}</ref> Jammeh refused to step down and the deadline passed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal troops move to Gambia border as Jammeh faces ultimatum|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/38672840|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 January 2017|date=19 January 2017}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref> On 18 January, parliament voted to extend Jammeh's term by three months,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKBN1521MH|title=Gambia's parliament extends defeated president's office by 3 months \u2013 Top News |agency=Reuters|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> while in parallel, [[Adama Barrow]] was internationally recognised as President.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-38675741|title=Gambia crisis: Barrow sworn in <!-- not a mistake -->in Senegal as Jammeh stays put|date=19 January 2017|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> On 19 January, Senegalese troops entered The Gambia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38682184 |title=Gambia crisis: Senegal sends in troops to back elected leader |accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> The [[United Nations Security Council]] approved a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2337|resolution]] backing Barrow while calling on Jammeh to step down. It backed ECOWAS' efforts to ensure that the results of the 2016 presidential election were respected by using political means first.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/un-adopts-resolution-backing-gambias-new-president-barrow/2017/01/19/df6a7166-de76-11e6-8902-610fe486791c_story.html |title=UN adopts resolution backing Gambia's new President Barrow |work=The Washington Post |date=19 January 2017 |accessdate=19 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119225520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/un-adopts-resolution-backing-gambias-new-president-barrow/2017/01/19/df6a7166-de76-11e6-8902-610fe486791c_story.html |archivedate=19 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Senegal halted its offensive, to allow mediation of the crisis one final time, with the invasion to proceed at noon on 20 January if Jammeh were to refuse to relinquish power.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/west-african-military-halt-gambia-operation--issue-jammeh-deadline/42861726|title=West African military halt Gambia operation, issue Jammeh deadline|agency=Reuters|publisher=Swissinfo|date=19 January 2017|access-date=19 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120024924/http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/west-african-military-halt-gambia-operation--issue-jammeh-deadline/42861726|archive-date=20 January 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jammeh again refused to step down and missed two deadlines on 20 January while regional leaders tried to persuade him to step down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/20/gambia-yahya-jammeh-midday-deadline-troops|title=The Gambia: Jammeh ignores two more deadlines to quit|work=The Guardian|date=20 January 2017|author=Ruth Maclean|access-date=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early hours of 21 January, Jammeh announced on state television that he was stepping down from the post of President,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Yahya Jammeh confirms he will step down|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/gambia-yahya-jammeh-agrees-step-170120184330091.html|accessdate=20 January 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Jammeh, facing military pressure, says steps down|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15505N?il=0|accessdate=21 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref> and left the country later on the same day, travelling to [[Guinea]] and then [[Equatorial Guinea]].<ref name=\"ReutersFlies\">{{cite news |first1=Tim |last1=Cocks |first2=Lamin |last2=Jahateh |title=Gambia's former leader Jammeh flies into exile in Equatorial Guinea |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN15505N|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=\"JammehLeavesBBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38706426 |title=Ex-President Yahya Jammeh leaves The Gambia after losing election |date=22 January 2016 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n=== Sexual Abuse and Rape Allegations ===\n\nThree women from Gambia accused the former president, Yahya Jammeh, of raping and sexually abusing them while still in office, as per rights advocacy group [[Human Rights Watch]] and TRIAL International.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/06/26/gambia-women-accuse-ex-president-sexual-violence|title=Gambia: Women Accuse Ex-President of Sexual Violence|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> According to ex-Gambian officials, women were pressured by presidential aides regularly to visit and work for Jammeh. One of the women is a Gambian pageant winner who has accused the ex-president of raping her. The victim, Fatou \"Toufah\" Jallow said she met Jammeh when she was 18 years old after winning a beauty pageant in 2014.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/jun/26/gambian-beauty-queen-accuses-ex-president-yahya-jammeh-of-rape|title=Gambian pageant winner accuses ex-president Yahya Jammeh of rape|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{ cite_web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/9/19/gambia_truth_reconciliation_commission_atrocities|title=Meet the Beauty Queen Who Inspired Gambia's Me Too Movement After Accusing Ex-Dictator of Rape | accessdate=19 September 2019|publisher=Democracy Now!}}</ref>\n\nAs per Jallow, in the months that followed, Jammeh asked her to marry him at a dinner organized by one of his aides. Later, Fatou was invited by the former president via his aide to attend a religious ceremony at the State House. However, on her arrival the victim claims to have been taken to the president\u2019s private residence where she was injected with a needle and \u201csodomized\u201d.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-48779673|title=Gambia: Appeal after rape claim against ex-president Jammeh|accessdate=26 June 2019|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In October 2019, Jallow testified before Gambia\u2019s public \"Truth and Reconciliation Commission\" about the rape charges.<ref>{{ cite web |website=Democracy Now! |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/11/1/fatou_toufah_jallow_gambia_testimony|date=Nov 1, 2019|accessdate=Nov 2, 2019|title=\"It Was Necessary\": Gambian Beauty Queen Returns Home to Testify About Rape By Former Dictator}}</ref>\n\n== Exile ==\nAs Jammeh left Gambia on 21 January 2017, Barrow stated that a \"[[Truth, Reconciliation and Reparations Commission|truth and reconciliation commission]]\" would be appointed to investigate any possible crimes committed by Jammeh. Barrow cautioned that the commission wouldn't prosecute Jammeh, only investigate the alleged crimes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adama Barrow pledges truth commission over Yahya Jammeh|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/adama-barrow-yahya-jammeh-leaving-guinea-170121175618203.html|accessdate=22 January 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> West African leaders did not guarantee any form of immunity to Jammeh.<ref>{{cite news|title=No immunity deal agreed for Gambia's Jammeh, Senegal minister says|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN1560LF?il=0|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=22 January 2017}}</ref> The United Nations, [[African Union]] and ECOWAS declared that any country offering refuge to him or his family would not be punished and he should be free to return to the country in the future. The statement added that it would work with the government of The Gambia to make sure that assets and properties legally belonging to him or his family, cabinet members, government officials or party supporters would not be seized.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's defeated leader Yahya Jammeh goes into exile |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/22/gambias-defeated-leader-yahya-jammeh-goes-exile/|accessdate=22 January 2017|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Jammeh later left Gambia for [[Equatorial Guinea]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's former leader Jammeh flies into exile in Equatorial Guinea |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN15505N|accessdate=22 January 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref> where he allegedly<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambia's Ousted Dictator Is Living the Good Life in a Palace in Equatorial Guinea|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/04/03/gambias-ousted-dictator-is-living-the-good-life-in-a-palace-in-equatorial-guinea/|accessdate=23 September 2019|publisher=Foreign Policy}}</ref> lives in a mansion in the village of [[Mongomo]].\n\nAfter Jammeh went in exile, Adama Barrow's special adviser Mai Ahmad Fatty alleged that in late January 2017, Jammeh had stolen {{currency|11.4|USD}} million from the state's treasury and used a cargo plane to ship out his luxury vehicles during his last week in power. He added that the state's treasury was virtually empty, which was confirmed by technicians in the [[Minister of Finance and Economic Affairs (Gambia)|Ministry of Finance]] as well as the [[Central Bank of the Gambia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/23/exiled-former-president-yahya-jammeh-stole-gambia|title=Exiled former president Yahya Jammeh 'stole $11.4m' from the Gambia|date=23 January 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=25 February 2017|author=Jason Burke}}</ref> About a month later, two senior ministers alleged that he had siphoned at least $50 million from social security, ports, and the national telecoms company. They also alleged that his private jet, which cost $4.5 million, was bought using the state's pension fund. The government stated that his actions had left the country with a debt of more than $1 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/23/the-gambia-debt-theft-mismanagement-jammeh-allegations|title=New claims over scale of ex-Gambian leader's theft from state coffers|date=23 February 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=25 February 2017|author=Ruth Maclean, Saikou Jammeh}}</ref> [[Reuters]] released a report regarding Jammeh's charity on 24 February 2017 in which it stated that funds from the Jammeh Foundation for Peace went to Jammeh himself, not to the foundation's projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-jammeh-idUSKBN16312M|title=Exclusive: How money flowed to Gambia's ex president|date=24 February 2017|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> The Minister of Justice announced on 10 March that the government would launch an investigation into his finances including his personal use of a charity bank account.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/gambia-probe-jammehs-finances/|title=Gambia to probe Jammeh's finances|date=10 March 2017|publisher=The Nation|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA Gambian court [[asset freezing|froze]] Jammeh's known remaining assets in The Gambia in May 2017 after it emerged he had siphoned off $50 million of public money through the state-owned telecommunications company [[Gamtel]] to his own bank accounts during his presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/gambian-authorities-seize-ex-president-jammehs-bank-accounts/a-38944380 |title=Gambian authorities seize ex-president Jammeh's bank accounts}}</ref>\n\nEffective December 21, 2017, US President [[Donald Trump]] issued an executive order under the [[Magnitsky Act]] that specifically named Yahya Jammeh among the persons whose US-based assets are to be blocked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/executive-order-blocking-property-persons-involved-serious-human-rights-abuse-corruption/|title=Executive Order Blocking the Property of Persons Involved in Serious Human Rights Abuse or Corruption|last=Trump|first=Donald|date=21 December 2017|website=Whitehouse.gov|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20171221.aspx|title=Issuance of Global Magnitsky Executive Order; Global Magnitsky Designations|last=|first=|date=|website=Treasury.gov|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn June 2018, the Gambian government decided to auction off his fleet of luxury cars and aircraft to raise money for health and education projects.\n\nOn 12 January 2020, Jammeh was warned not to return to Gambia without permission, as his safety couldn't be guaranteed, a government spokesman told the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51082371|title=Yahya Jammeh warned not to return to The Gambia|website=BBC|date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Yahya Jammeh with Obamas 2014.jpg|thumb|300px|Yahya and [[Zeinab Jammeh]] with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] in the [[White House]], August 2014.]]\n\n=== Marriages ===\n\nJammeh is an ethnic [[Jola people|Jola]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A shock victory for the underdog in Gambia|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21711208-old-style-african-despot-does-right-thing-and-goes-shock-victory|accessdate=9 December 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> Jammeh briefly dated Tuti Faal, of [[Mauritania]]n descent, in 1994 before marrying her. She worked for the Gambia Telecommunication Company (GAMTEL) until the coup in July 1994. They had difficulty conceiving a child, and in 1998 Jammeh sent her to [[Saudi Arabia]] for a [[Gynaecology|gynaecological]] exam, and during her time abroad, divorced her.<ref name=DO21 /> Jammeh married his second wife [[Zeinab Jammeh|Zeinab (Zineb) Suma Jammeh]], on 26 March 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yahya Jammeh Wife: Who Is Married To The Gambian President |url=http://www.morningledger.com/yahya-jammeh-wife-gambian-president/13129506 |website=Morning Ledger |accessdate=18 January 2017 |date=16 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228000046/http://www.morningledger.com/yahya-jammeh-wife-gambian-president/13129506/ |archive-date=28 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=DO21 /><ref>[https://twitter.com/ZinebJammeh/status/581186451859177472 Happy 16th wedding Anniversary to my beloved husband. May GOD The ALMIGHTY continue to bless our union for ever.], First Lady of Gambia on Twitter, 26 March 2015.</ref> They have two children as of 2007, a daughter, Mariam Jammeh, and a son, Muhammed Yahya Jammeh. The latter was born in late 2007, when his daughter was eight years old.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090621141453/http://www.statehouse.gm/babymuhamed-christening_311207.htm Christening of Baby Muhammed Yahya Jammeh], Office of the Gambian President website, 31 December 2007.</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2010, Jammeh announced his marriage to a 21-year-old (or possibly 18-year-old<ref name=FNdiv />) additional wife by the name Alima Sallah, daughter of Omar Gibril Sallah, Gambia's Ambassador to Saudi Arabia, and Zahra Sallah.<ref name=DO21>[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-marries-second-wife President Jammeh Marries Second Wife] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727171922/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammeh-marries-second-wife |date=27 July 2011 }}, ''Daily Observer'', 4 October 2010.</ref><ref name=GNow21>[http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambian-president-takes-21-year-old-Alima-Sallah-as-second-wife.html Gambian president takes 21 year old Alima Sallah as second wife] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315181652/http://www.gambianow.com/news/News/Gambian-president-takes-21-year-old-Alima-Sallah-as-second-wife.html |date=15 March 2012 }}, ''Gambia News'', 3 October 2010.</ref> It was announced that his new wife would officially be referred to as Lady Alima Yahya Jammeh, and would not be referred to as a \"first lady\", since Zeinab Suma Jammeh is the official \"first lady\".<ref name=GNow21 />\n\nAccording to at least one source, his marriage to Ms. Sallah was a shock to his other wife Zeinab Suma Jammeh, and the additional marriage led to strains in their relationship and even plans for their divorce.<ref name=MBai>M'Bai, P. N., [https://web.archive.org/web/20100702235302/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5364/Breaking-News-Gambia-SECOND-FIRST-LADY-ALIMA-SALLAH-ARRIVES-IN-USAMIDST-MOUNTING-TENSIONS-IN-KANILAI-/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia: Second First Lady Alima Sallah Arrives in U. S. \u2013 Amidst Mounting Tensions in Kanilai] ''Freedom Newspaper'', 28 June 2010.</ref> Zeinab Jammeh had reportedly already been living in the US separately from her husband for some time.<ref name=MBai /> Ms. Sallah reportedly also left Gambia for the US in June 2010.<ref name=MBai /> According to the same publication, he then divorced Ms. Sallah in early 2011.<ref name=FNdiv>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110430163742/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/6099/Breaking-News--Gambia--JAMMEH-DIVORCES-FIRST-LADY-ALIMA-SALLAH/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia \u2013 Jammeh Divorces First Lady Alima Sallah], ''Freedom Now Newspaper'' online, 26 April 2011.</ref><ref name=FNvisit>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110623221056/http://freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/6406/Gambia--Breaking-News-FIRST-LADY-JAMMEH-TO-VISIT-US-NEXT-WEEK/Default.aspx Breaking News: Gambia \u2013 First Lady Jammeh to Visit us Next Week], ''Freedom Now Newspaper'' online, 18 June 2011. HE reportedly tied the knot with a 22-year-old charming Ghanaian lady in Kumasi last weekend.\n\nMrs. Nora Jammeh, formerly called Munira Yahaya, a graduate of Sunyani Polytechnic, was engaged to the Gambian president two weeks ago in the Gambia, which was followed by the secret wedding at the Golden Tulip Hotel in Kumasi in 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n\nJammeh, [[Islam in the Gambia|like the majority of Gambians]], practices Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammehs-bbc-interview|title=\"President Jammeh's BBC interview\" (reprinted in the Daily Observer, Gambia, 13 December 2011)|accessdate=4 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104083346/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/president-jammehs-bbc-interview|archivedate=4 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2010, Jammeh stressed that people should believe in God: \"If you don't believe in God, you can never be grateful to humanity and you are even below a pig.\"<ref>Ndow, M., and Fadera, H., [http://allafrica.com/stories/201007270096.html Democracy of Exploitation Will Never Happen in This Country], ''The Daily Observer'' (Banjul), 26 July 2010.</ref> In 2011 he told the BBC, \"I will deliver to the Gambian people and if I have to rule this country for one billion years, I will, if Allah says so.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16148458|title=Gambia's Yahya Jammeh ready for 'billion-year' rule|date=12 December 2011|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 12 December 2015, Jammeh declared the Muslim-majority country to be an [[Islamic republic]], saying the move marked a break with the Gambia's colonial past. Jammeh told state TV that the proclamation was in line with Gambia's \"religious identity and values\". He added that no dress code would be imposed and citizens of other faiths would be allowed to practice freely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-35082343?post_id=844307525644381_949085868499879|title=Gambia declared Islamic republic by President Yahya Jammeh|date=12 December 2015|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n== Titles and styles ==\n\nThe official title used was His Excellency Sheikh Professor Alhaji Dr. Yahya Abdul-Aziz Awal Jemus Junkung Jammeh Naasiru Deen Babili Mansa.<ref>[http://www.un.org/en/ga/64/generaldebate/pdf/GM_en pdf]</ref> He was Commander in Chief of The Armed Forces and Chief Custodian of the Sacred Constitution of the Gambia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020106144503/http://www.statehouse.gm/president.html Republic of The Gambia State House Online: Office of the President], Republic of the Gambia government website.</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2015, a statement from the [[State House of the Gambia|State House]] stated that President Jammeh should be addressed as \"[[Excellency|His Excellency]] [[Sheikh]] Professor [[Hajji|Alhaji]] Dr. Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh Babili Mansa\".<ref>{{cite press release |date=16 June 2015 |title=PRESIDENT TO BE ADDRESSED AS HIS EXCELLENCY SHEIKH PROFESSOR ALHAJI DR. YAHYA A.J.J. JAMMEH BABILI MANSA |url=http://www.statehouse.gm/Press-releases/presi-title-addressed-with-babili-mansa-effective-17th-june_16062015.htm |location=Banjui |publisher=State House of the Gambia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619174146/http://www.statehouse.gm/Press-releases/presi-title-addressed-with-babili-mansa-effective-17th-june_16062015.htm |archivedate=19 June 2015 |access-date=19 June 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The title ''Babili Mansa'', which the President decided to drop in December 2014, is a phrase in the [[Mandinka language]] that could be translated as either \"Chief Bridge Builder\" or \"Conqueror of Rivers\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-33180471 |title=Gambia's President Jammeh gets extra title of 'bridge builder' |date=18 June 2015 |website= |publisher=BBC News |access-date=19 June 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.starafrica.com/news/gambia-president-jammeh-ditches-babili-mansa-title.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619195158/http://en.starafrica.com/news/gambia-president-jammeh-ditches-babili-mansa-title.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 June 2015 |title=Gambia: President Jammeh ditches Babili Mansa title |publisher= StarAfrica|access-date=19 June 2015  }}</ref> Two months before, he had already removed the title ''Nasirul Deen'' (\"Defender of the Faith\"), which had been conferred to him by the [[Gambia Supreme Islamic Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/jammeh-retakes-babili-mansa-title|title= Jammeh retakes 'Babili Mansa' title|date=17 June 2015 |work=The Point |access-date= 19 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nJammeh has received honorary doctorates from [[Saint Mary's University (Halifax)|Saint Mary's University]] of Halifax in 1999 for providing his citizens \"freedom to pursue their well-being, and to live in peace and harmony\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smu.ca/newsreleases/1999/gambiacit.html|title=Citation for President Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh on the Occasion of Presenting Him for the Degree of Doctor of Civil Law (Honoris Causa)|date=16 February 1999|publisher=Saint Mary's University|access-date=22 January 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130115124407/http://www.smu.ca/newsreleases/1999/gambiacit.html|archive-date=15 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[St. Mary's College of Maryland]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smcm.edu/news/2015/06/message-from-the-president-st-marys-colleges-peace-program/|title=Message from the President: St. Mary's College's PEACE Program \u2013 SMCM Newsroom|date=24 June 2015|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201207060986.html|title=Gambia: St Mary's College Students Observe U.S. Independence Day|first=Sheriff|last=Janko|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=26 November 2016|via=AllAfrica}}</ref> [[Universidad Empresarial de Costa Rica]], Norman Academy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grts.gm/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:grts-radio-news-may-23-2012&catid=39:news&Itemid=75|title=GRTS Radio News May 23, 2012|author=Buba Bojang|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> and [[National Taipei University of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statehouse.gm/Taiwan-state-visit-itinerary_26062012.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123111117/http://www.statehouse.gm/Taiwan-state-visit-itinerary_26062012.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2013|title=Office of The Gambian President: State House Online: Yahya A.J.J. Jammeh|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe has also received dubious awards through the [[International Parliament for Safety and Peace]], an [[List of unrecognized higher education accreditation organizations|unrecognised higher education accreditation organisation]]. Among these was a [[Nebraska Admiral]] certificate; however, Rae Hein, a spokeswoman for the [[List of governors of Nebraska|Governor of Nebraska]], stated \"We regret that this individual has attempted to embellish a certificate for a Nebraska admiralship, claiming that it was a high honour bestowed upon him by the governor, when to the best of our knowledge, this person has no relationship with or ties to Nebraska.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpj.org/security/2010/09/jammeh-award-coverage-reflects-chill-over-gambian.php|title=Jammeh 'award' coverage reflects chill in Gambian press \u2013 Committee to Protect Journalists|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201009271763.html |title=Gambia: Jammeh 'Award' Coverage Reflects Chill in Press |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first = Ishaan | last = Tharoor | url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2010/10/01/when-was-the-gambian-president-the-admiral-of-nebraska/ | title = When Was the Gambian President the Admiral of Nebraska? | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=2010-10-01 | accessdate = 2014-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5606/Breaking-News-Gambia-Governors-Office-Confirms-Authenticity-Of-Naval-Award-Extended-To-Jammeh/Default.aspx |title=Governor's Office Confirms Authenticity Of Naval Award |author=Pa Nderry M\u2019Bai |publisher=Freedom Newspaper Online (Freedomnewspaper.com) |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205254/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5606/Breaking-News-Gambia-Governors-Office-Confirms-Authenticity-Of-Naval-Award-Extended-To-Jammeh/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5644/Breaking-News-Gambia-THE-MAN-BEHIND-JAMMEHS-NEBRASKA--ADMIRAL-ADWARD-SPEAKS/Default.aspx |title=The Man Behind Jammeh's Nebraska Admiral Award Speaks |author=Pa Nderry M\u2019Bai |publisher=Freedom Newspaper Online (Freedomnewspaper.com) |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205306/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5644/Breaking-News-Gambia-THE-MAN-BEHIND-JAMMEHS-NEBRASKA--ADMIRAL-ADWARD-SPEAKS/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=freedom>{{cite news|title=Remove Yaya Jammeh from office|first=Ansu|last=Koroma|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5623/Gambia--Remove-Yaya-Jammeh-from-officeWrites-Ansu-Koroma/Default.aspx|date=2010-09-25|accessdate=2011-03-02|quote=It came to light that this award was initiated by Yaya Jammeh and brought to fruition by two individuals who claim to represent an Italian-based organization called International Parliament for Safety and Peace \u2013 an organization, according to a [[Committee to Protect Journalists|CPJ]] release, has been accused in the past for providing credentials to educational institutions otherwise not accredited in their own nations, and of selling membership, titles and other distinctions for fees. It stands to reason that Yaya Jammeh must have paid a fee to these characters, one of whom carries the title of Ambassador. [...] The second impeachable offense that Yaya Jammeh has committed is during the same award ceremony, involving the same characters who claim to be representing the International Parliament for Safety and Peace, is the claim that two awards he received were accompanied by a letter from 'President [[Barack Obama|Barrak Obama]] [sic] commending the Gambian leader for the accolade, and also commended him for helping address the most pressing needs in his community'.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224094813/http://freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5623/Gambia--Remove-Yaya-Jammeh-from-officeWrites-Ansu-Koroma/Default.aspx|archivedate=24 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=omaha>{{cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20101002/NEWS01/710029839|accessdate=2011-03-02|title=Nebraska Navy has 'unsavory despot'|quote=Last month, the certificate was delivered to Jammeh by a representative of the International Parliament for Safety and Peace, an Italian organization that has drawn criticism for recognizing diploma mills. The group also passed along two other \u201cawards\u201d to Jammeh, purportedly from President Barack Obama. A U.S. State Department official said Friday that the White House had no connection with those awards. Jammeh's honors were publicized in the Gambian press and soon drew attention from outside groups. The Committee to Protect Journalists initially was concerned that Obama and others were giving awards to Jammeh but later concluded that no honors were intended. The admiralship isn't Jammeh's first state award: Kentucky's governor made him an honorary \u201cKentucky colonel\u201d in 2008.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130130182846/http://www.omaha.com/article/20101002/NEWS01/710029839|archivedate=30 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=bags>{{cite news|title=Gambia: President Jammeh Bags Four Awards|date=2010-09-17|quote=The Gambian leader, His Excellency Sheikh Professor Alhaji Dr Yahya Jammeh was Thursday presented with four different prestigious awards from the International Parliament for Safety and Peace (IPSP) upon its various initiatives in the United States of America and the Federal Republic of Germany, during a presentation ceremony held at State House in Banjul. [...] The awards include the 'President's Volunteer Call to Service Award', and the 'Platinum Award 2009 by President Barack Obama'. The last two awards are the 'Admiral of the Great Navy of the State of Nebraska', USA', given to the Gambian leader by its Governor, Dave Heinemana, whilst the fourth award, the 'Honorary Vocational Bachelors Degree' was given by the Printers and Publishers Guild of Northern Germany.}}</ref> IPSP representatives also gave Jammeh two awards and a letter from [[Barack Obama]]<ref name=bags/><ref name=Epoch>{{cite news|title=\u300a\u5916\u4ea4\u653f\u7b56\u300b\ufe55\u4eba\u6743\u8df5\u8e0f\u8005\u7684\"\u548c\u5e73\u5956\"|url=http://www.epochtimes.com/gb/10/12/13/n3112016.htm|work=[[Epoch Times]]|date=2010-12-13|accessdate=2010-12-15|trans-title=\"Foreign Policy\": human rights abuses by the \"Peace Prize\"| quote=\u5188\u6bd4\u4e9a\u603b\u7edf\u53f6\u6d77\u4e9a\u2027\u8d3e\u6885\uff08Yahya Jammeh\uff09\u4eca\u5e74\u65e9\u4e9b\u65f6\u5019\u58f0\u79f0\u6536\u5230\u4e86\u4f17\u591a\u5956\u9879\uff0c\u6ca1\u6709\u592a\u591a\u7684\u8c03\u67e5\uff0c\u751a\u81f3\u4e0d\u7528\u5f88\u591a\u8c37\u6b4c\u641c\u7d22\uff0c\u5c31\u80fd\u786e\u5b9a\u5b83\u7684\u771f\u5b9e\u6027\u4e0e\u5426\u3002\u9996\u5148\u9881\u5956\u673a\u6784\u662f\u4e0d\u660e\u4e0d\u767d\u7684\u201c\u56fd\u9645\u5b89\u5168\u4e0e\u548c\u5e73\u8bae\u4f1a\u201d(International Parliament for Safety and Peace)\uff0c\u5176\u6b21\u662f\u7535\u5b50\u5783\u573e\u90ae\u4ef6\u822c\u7684\u5f97\u5956\u540d\u5934\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\u5305\u62ec\u201c\u5fd7\u613f\u670d\u52a1\u603b\u7edf\u5956\u201d\u3001\u201c\u5df4\u62c9\u514b\u2027\u5965\u5df4\u9a6c\u603b\u7edf2009\u767d\u91d1\u5956\u201d\uff0c\u8fd8\u6709\u4ee4\u4eba\u8d28\u7591\u7684\u201c\u8363\u8a89\u804c\u4e1a\u5b66\u58eb\u5b66\u4f4d\u201d\uff0c\u7531\u5fb7\u56fd\u5317\u90e8\u7684\u51fa\u7248\u5546\u534f\u4f1a(Printers and Publishers Guild)\u9881\u53d1\u7684\u3002}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721031822/http://www.gov.gm/egov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=182%3Apres-awards&catid=14%3Anews&Itemid=1 ]</ref> that were later described as inauthentic or non-existent.<ref name=freedom/><ref name=omaha/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5622/Breaking-News-Gambia--Obama-Govt-Says-Daily-Observer-Award-Story-Is-False/Default.aspx |title=Welcome to Freedom Newspaper Online |publisher=Freedomnewspaper.com |accessdate=19 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008205344/http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/Homepage/tabid/36/mid/367/newsid367/5622/Breaking-News-Gambia--Obama-Govt-Says-Daily-Observer-Award-Story-Is-False/Default.aspx |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/36643 |title=afrol News \u2013 Gambia Dictator \"lied about Obama award\" |publisher=Afrol.com |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nhpr.org/gambian-leader-claims-fictitious-awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808201114/http://www.nhpr.org/gambian-leader-claims-fictitious-awards |title= Gambian Leader Claims Fictitious Awards |archivedate= 8 August 2011 |accessdate= 24 June 2017 |via= archive.org |first=J.J. |last= Sutherland |date= 29 September 2010}}</ref> Jammeh also received \"[[Russia]]n\" and \"[[Germany|German]]\" honorary degrees from members of the IPSP.<ref name=bags/><ref name=Epoch/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://allafrica.com/stories/201007060551.html |title=Gambia: Russian University Awards Doctorate Degree to President Jammeh |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Depiction on Gambian currency==\nYahya Jammeh's portrait is depicted on some of the [[Gambian dalasi]] banknotes; 2014 [[polymer]] 20 Dalasis [[banknote]] commemorating 20 Years of his regime. The N.D. (2015) issue banknotes - 5 Dalasis up to 200 Dalasis.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last=Hughes |first=Arnold |year=2000 |title='Democra