{"title_page": "Constand Viljoen", "text_new": "{{short description|South African military officer and politician}}\n{{Use South African English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Constand Viljoen\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=ZAR|size=100%|sep=,|SSAG|SD|SOE|SM52|MMM}}\n| image               = General Constand Viljoen.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = \n| order2              = \n| office2             = [[Leader]] of the [[Freedom Front Plus|Freedom Front]]\n| term_start2         = 1 March 1994\n| term_end2           = 26 June 2001\n| predecessor2        = ''Party established''\n| successor2          = [[Pieter Mulder]]\n| office3             = [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]\n| term_start3         = 1994\n| term_end3           = 2001\n| president3          = [[Nelson Mandela]]<br />[[Thabo Mbeki]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|df=yes|1933|10|28} - 3 April  2020}<ref name=\"omalley\">[http://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv02424/04lv02426/05lv02691.htm Viljoen, Constand Laubscher \u2013 The O'Malley Archives]</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Standerton]], [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|03|1933|10|28}}\n| death_place         = Ohrigstad, Limpopo, South Africa\n| restingplace        = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname           = Constand Laubscher Viljoen\n| party               = [[Freedom Front Plus]] (1994\u20132001)\n| otherparty          = [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] (pre-1994)\n| spouse              = Christina \"Ristie\" Heckroodt\n| relations           = Braam Viljoen (twin brother)\n| children            = 5\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Pretoria]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| signature           = \n| signature_alt       = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = <!--Military service-->\n| allegiance          = South Africa\n| branch              = [[South African Army]]\n| serviceyears        = 1956\u20131985\n| rank                = [[General]]\n| unit                = [[4 Artillery Regiment|4 Field Regiment]]\n| commands            = [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the SADF|Chief of the South African Defence Force]]<br/>[[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the Army|Chief of the Army]]<br/>Director General Operations<br/>[[South African Army College]]<br/>[[School of Artillery (South Africa)|School of Artillery]]\n| battles             = [[South African Border War]]<br/>[[Operation Savannah (Angola)|Operation Savannah]]\n| mawards             = [[Star of South Africa, Gold|Star of South Africa]]<br/>[[Southern Cross Decoration]]<br/>[[South African Police Star for Outstanding Service]]<br/>[[Southern Cross Medal (1952)|Southern Cross Medal]]<br/>[[Military Merit Medal (South Africa)|Military Merit Medal]]<br/>[[Order of the Cloud and Banner|Order of the Cloud and Banner with Grand Cordon]] (China)\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n[[General]] '''Constand Laubscher Viljoen''', {{post-nominals|country=ZAR|size=100%|sep=,|SSAG|SD|SOE|SM52|MMM}} (28 October 1933 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a [[List of South African military chiefs|South African military commander]] and politician. He co-founded the [[Afrikaner Volksfront]] (Afrikaner People's Front) and later founded the [[Freedom Front]] (now Freedom Front Plus).<ref>{{cite news |title=The who, why and what of South Africa\u2019s minority Afrikaner party |url=http://theconversation.com/the-who-why-and-what-of-south-africas-minority-afrikaner-party-116913 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Conversation |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> He is partly credited with having prevented the outbreak of armed violence by disaffected [[white South African]]s prior to post-[[apartheid]] [[1994 South African general election|general elections]].<ref name=Volkstaat>{{cite web|title=Gen. Constand Viljoen|url=http://www.volkstaat.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=757:constand-viljoen&catid=96:gen-constand-viljoen&Itemid=157|website=Volkstaat.net|publisher=Boerevolkstaat|accessdate=22 November 2014|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nViljoen matriculated at Standerton High School in 1951.<ref name=pressreader>{{cite news |title=Former SA defence force chief General Constand Viljoen fears for democracy in South Africa, but he wouldn't live elsewhere |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/the-sunday-independent/20140601/281745562438500 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[PressReader]] |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> He joined South Africa's pre-republic [[South African Defence Force|Union Defence Force]] in 1956 upon receiving a degree in military science at the [[University of Pretoria]].<ref name=\"omalley\" /> By 1974, Viljoen had been named the [[South African Army]]'s Director of General Operations, subsequently serving as the Principal Staff Officer to the [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the SADF|Chief of the South African Defence Force]].<ref name=pressreader/> He was appointed as [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the Army|Chief of the Army]] in 1977 and succeeded General [[Magnus Malan]] as Chief of the South African Defence Force in 1980.<ref name=DaysGen>{{cite book|last1=Hamann|first1=Hilton|title=Days of the Generals|date=2001|publisher=Zebra Press (Struck Publishers)|location=Cape Town|chapter=Introduction|isbn=1-86872-340-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mYgWcHq8lE8C}}</ref>{{Rp|xv}}\n\n===Angolan service===\nViljoen was the senior SADF military officer directing [[Operation Savannah (Angola)|Operation Savannah]] in 1975. He is also credited with planning the first major airborne assault in South African military history, [[Battle of Cassinga|Cassinga]], a raid carried out against [[SWAPO]] insurgents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Own Reporter |title=Apartheid brass blamed for Cassinga massacre |url=https://mg.co.za/article/1998-11-02-apartheid-brass-blamed-for-cassinga-massacre/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Mail Guardian |date=2 November 1998}}</ref> Despite his rank, Viljoen was present during the battle,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=13&set_id=1&art_id=vn20070519093038473C345664\n|title=Battle of Cassinga still rages |publisher=Independent Online |accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref> offering what was described as a \"swashbuckling\" front-line leadership, which won him the respect of many fellow [[Afrikaner]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/06/world/south-african-rightists-rally-behind-ex-generals.html |title=South African Rightists Rally Behind Ex-Generals |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=2009-04-29|first1=Bill|last1=Keller|date=1993-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nViljoen is credited by some with having made overtures which helped lead to [[white South African]]s' acceptance of universal suffrage and free elections, such as with his famous speech at the [[Broederbond]] annual assembly in [[Voortrekkerhoogte]], saying of the [[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black South African]]s in his army, ''As hulle kan veg vir Suid-Afrika, kan hulle stem vir Suid-Afrika!'' ([[Afrikaans]]: \"If they can fight for South Africa, then they can vote for South Africa!\").<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandela united a nation seeking national pride |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/weekend-argus-sunday-edition/20140511/281887296329149 |website=Pressreader |publisher=Weekend Argus (Sunday Edition) |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Viljoen and fellow retired generals formed the [[Afrikaner Volksfront]] (Afrikaner People's Front), an umbrella body for conservative Afrikaners. However, Viljoen reportedly had strained relationships with the leaders of other right-wing parties, who considered him too moderate.<ref>{{cite book|last=Waldmeir|first=Patti|title=Anatomy of a Miracle: The End of Apartheid and the Birth of the New South Africa|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2IHKD-FY8YgC|isbn=978-0-8135-2582-2|chapter=13: Battling for the Right|page=223}}</ref>\n\n===Bophuthatswana action and decision to contest elections===\n{{Main|Bophuthatswana coup d'\u00e9tat of 1994}}\nImmediately prior to the 1994 elections Viljoen had a force of between 50,000 and 60,000 trained paramilitary personnel at his command, with the ability to seize large sections of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=15&art_id=ct20021102190803396B510670&set_id=1|title=Soweto bombs may have been just a 'dry run'|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/990524/archive_001065.htm|title=Proving That One Man Can Make a Difference|publisher=US News & World Report|accessdate=2009-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013072623/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/990524/archive_001065.htm|archive-date=13 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The force was assembled in preparation for war with [[Umkhonto we Sizwe]], the military wing of the [[African National Congress]], as a potential contingency to protect Afrikaner interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?sf=13&set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20010324172513644P420166|title=Viljoen reveals just how close SA came to war|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1994, Viljoen led an effort by several thousand Volksfront militia to protect the [[bantustan]] president, [[Lucas Mangope]], in [[Bophuthatswana]] against a [[Bophuthatswana coup d'\u00e9tat of 1994|coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/11/world/homeland-leader-in-south-africa-flees-his-capital.html|title=Homeland Leader in South Africa Flees His Capital|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-11}}</ref> Despite being requested not to participate in the action because of extremist views, militants of the [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging]] also advanced into Bophuthatswana, sparking clashes with the security forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/12/world/mixed-signals-fatal-for-south-african-separatists.html|title=Mixed Signals Fatal for South African Separatists|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-12}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after the incident, Viljoen split from the Volksfront<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940313&slug=1899838|title=South Africa Takes Control Of Homeland \u2013 Bophuthatswana's Ruler Removed To Open Up Election|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Tom| last=Cohen| date=1994-03-13}}</ref> and initiated a legitimate election campaign,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/13/world/a-homeland-s-agony.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2|title=A Homeland's Agony|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-13}}</ref> co-founding and becoming leader of the [[Freedom Front]] (''Vryheidsfront''), a new political party representing white conservatives. His decision to take part in the elections is believed to have prevented armed resistance by the far right and on the occasion of his retirement from politics, the South African government recognised him for preventing bloodshed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_996781,00.html|title=Mbeki thanks Constand Viljoen|publisher=News24|accessdate=2009-04-29}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nViljoen's decision was at least partly influenced by the mediation of his identical twin brother, [[Abraham Viljoen]] (Braam), who was an anti-apartheid activist while his brother led the military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1993/1028/28131.html|title=Abraham Viljoen: Longtime Campaigner For Black-White Solidarity in South Africa|publisher=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unisa.ac.za/default.asp?Cmd=ViewContent&ContentID=14555|title=Mediation during the Transition in South Afric|publisher=University of South Africa|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Post-apartheid South Africa===\nIn [[1994 South African general election|the election]], the Freedom Front, under the leadership of Viljoen, received 2.2% of the national vote and nine seats in the National Assembly. It became the strongest party outside [[Nelson Mandela]]'s Government of National Unity. Although his supporters were at odds with the government and the ANC, Viljoen praised Mandela on the occasion of his retreat from politics in 1999, even ending his Parliamentary speech speaking in Mandela's native language, [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]: ''Go rest in peace. Go rest in the shadow of a tree at your home''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Foes pay tribute as Mandela begins long goodbye |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/27/nelsonmandela |accessdate=3 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 March 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Viljoen handed over the leadership of the Freedom Front to [[Pieter Mulder]] and retired from politics, citing his frustration working with a parliament dominated by the ANC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/1223061.stm|title=Constand Viljoen to leave SA parliament|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-04-29| date=2001-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==After retirement==\nIn 2003, it emerged that Viljoen had been a target of the [[Boeremag]] paramilitary right-wing group, which considered him a traitor who had underhandedly sold out the Afrikaner people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=qw1067593321550B263|title=Was the TAU part of the Boeremag plot?|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Viljoen, aged 74, put up what was described as a spirited fight against two would-be muggers, who were subsequently arrested.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/ex-sandf-chief-turns-table-on-muggers-1.400904#.UXGgNsoYq9s|title=Ex-SANDF chief turns tables on muggers|publisher=IOL News|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>\n==Death==\nCurrent Freedom Front Plus leader [[Pieter Groenewald]] announced on 3 April 2020 that Viljoen had died on his farm in [[Ohrigstad]], [[Limpopo]]. He was 86 and was surrounded by his children. Viljoen died of natural causes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Toit |first1=Pieter |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-general-constand-viljoen-former-sadf-commander-and-political-leader-dies-at-86-20200403 |title=General Constand Viljoen, former SADF commander and political leader, dies at 86 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |agency=News24 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe is survived by his wife Christina Susanna Heckroodt, four sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite news |title=General Constand Viljoen passes away aged 86 |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-general-constand-viljoen-former-sadf-commander-and-political-leader-dies-at-86-20200403 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n* {{Medal Display|SSAG}}\n* {{Medal Display|SD}}\n* {{Medal Display|SOE}}\n* {{Medal Display|SM52}}\n* {{Medal Display|MMM}}\n* {{Medal Display|PP}}\n* {{Medal Display|GoodServiceG}}\n* {{Medal Display|GoodServiceS}}\n* {{Medal Display|PFGS}}\n* {{Medal Display|ORB2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new | reason =  New Party}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus|Freedom Front]] | years = 1994\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft | after = Dr [[Pieter Mulder]]  }}\n|-\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Magnus Malan]] |rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Chief of the [[South African Defence Force]]| | years = 1980\u20131985}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Johannes Geldenhuys]] |rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = Chief of the [[South African Army]]| | years = 1976\u20131980}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = JW van Niekerk}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Officer Commanding [[South African Army College]]| | years = 1968\u20131969}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Johan Potgieter]] }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Hendrik Greyvenstein]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Officer Commanding [[School of Artillery (South Africa)|School of Artillery]]| | years = 1966\u20131968}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Shorty Brown]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Helm Roos]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[School of Artillery (South Africa)|Chief Instructor Gunnery]]| | years = 1962\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft | after = John Albert Reid Cox}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SA Defence Chiefs}}\n{{SA Army Chiefs}}{{Freedom Front Plus}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Viljoen, Constand}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Krugersdorp]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:South African anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of the South African Army]]\n[[Category:South African military personnel of the Border War]]\n[[Category:Freedom Front Plus politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African military officer and politician}}\n{{Use South African English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Constand Viljoen\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=ZAR|size=100%|sep=,|SSAG|SD|SOE|SM52|MMM}}\n| image               = General Constand Viljoen.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = \n| order2              = \n| office2             = [[Leader]] of the [[Freedom Front Plus|Freedom Front]]\n| term_start2         = 1 March 1994\n| term_end2           = 26 June 2001\n| predecessor2        = ''Party established''\n| successor2          = [[Pieter Mulder]]\n| office3             = [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]\n| term_start3         = 1994\n| term_end3           = 2001\n| president3          = [[Nelson Mandela]]<br />[[Thabo Mbeki]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|df=yes|1933|10|28}}<ref name=\"omalley\">[http://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv02424/04lv02426/05lv02691.htm Viljoen, Constand Laubscher \u2013 The O'Malley Archives]</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Standerton]], [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|03|1933|10|28}}\n| death_place         = Ohrigstad, Limpopo, South Africa\n| restingplace        = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname           = Constand Laubscher Viljoen\n| party               = [[Freedom Front Plus]] (1994\u20132001)\n| otherparty          = [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] (pre-1994)\n| spouse              = Christina \"Ristie\" Heckroodt\n| relations           = Braam Viljoen (twin brother)\n| children            = 5\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Pretoria]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| signature           = \n| signature_alt       = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = <!--Military service-->\n| allegiance          = South Africa\n| branch              = [[South African Army]]\n| serviceyears        = 1956\u20131985\n| rank                = [[General]]\n| unit                = [[4 Artillery Regiment|4 Field Regiment]]\n| commands            = [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the SADF|Chief of the South African Defence Force]]<br/>[[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the Army|Chief of the Army]]<br/>Director General Operations<br/>[[South African Army College]]<br/>[[School of Artillery (South Africa)|School of Artillery]]\n| battles             = [[South African Border War]]<br/>[[Operation Savannah (Angola)|Operation Savannah]]\n| mawards             = [[Star of South Africa, Gold|Star of South Africa]]<br/>[[Southern Cross Decoration]]<br/>[[South African Police Star for Outstanding Service]]<br/>[[Southern Cross Medal (1952)|Southern Cross Medal]]<br/>[[Military Merit Medal (South Africa)|Military Merit Medal]]<br/>[[Order of the Cloud and Banner|Order of the Cloud and Banner with Grand Cordon]] (China)\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n[[General]] '''Constand Laubscher Viljoen''', {{post-nominals|country=ZAR|size=100%|sep=,|SSAG|SD|SOE|SM52|MMM}} (28 October 1933 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a [[List of South African military chiefs|South African military commander]] and politician. He co-founded the [[Afrikaner Volksfront]] (Afrikaner People's Front) and later founded the [[Freedom Front]] (now Freedom Front Plus).<ref>{{cite news |title=The who, why and what of South Africa\u2019s minority Afrikaner party |url=http://theconversation.com/the-who-why-and-what-of-south-africas-minority-afrikaner-party-116913 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Conversation |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> He is partly credited with having prevented the outbreak of armed violence by disaffected [[white South African]]s prior to post-[[apartheid]] [[1994 South African general election|general elections]].<ref name=Volkstaat>{{cite web|title=Gen. Constand Viljoen|url=http://www.volkstaat.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=757:constand-viljoen&catid=96:gen-constand-viljoen&Itemid=157|website=Volkstaat.net|publisher=Boerevolkstaat|accessdate=22 November 2014|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nViljoen matriculated at Standerton High School in 1951.<ref name=pressreader>{{cite news |title=Former SA defence force chief General Constand Viljoen fears for democracy in South Africa, but he wouldn't live elsewhere |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/the-sunday-independent/20140601/281745562438500 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[PressReader]] |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> He joined South Africa's pre-republic [[South African Defence Force|Union Defence Force]] in 1956 upon receiving a degree in military science at the [[University of Pretoria]].<ref name=\"omalley\" /> By 1974, Viljoen had been named the [[South African Army]]'s Director of General Operations, subsequently serving as the Principal Staff Officer to the [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the SADF|Chief of the South African Defence Force]].<ref name=pressreader/> He was appointed as [[List of South African military chiefs#Chief of the Army|Chief of the Army]] in 1977 and succeeded General [[Magnus Malan]] as Chief of the South African Defence Force in 1980.<ref name=DaysGen>{{cite book|last1=Hamann|first1=Hilton|title=Days of the Generals|date=2001|publisher=Zebra Press (Struck Publishers)|location=Cape Town|chapter=Introduction|isbn=1-86872-340-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mYgWcHq8lE8C}}</ref>{{Rp|xv}}\n\n===Angolan service===\nViljoen was the senior SADF military officer directing [[Operation Savannah (Angola)|Operation Savannah]] in 1975. He is also credited with planning the first major airborne assault in South African military history, [[Battle of Cassinga|Cassinga]], a raid carried out against [[SWAPO]] insurgents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Own Reporter |title=Apartheid brass blamed for Cassinga massacre |url=https://mg.co.za/article/1998-11-02-apartheid-brass-blamed-for-cassinga-massacre/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Mail Guardian |date=2 November 1998}}</ref> Despite his rank, Viljoen was present during the battle,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=13&set_id=1&art_id=vn20070519093038473C345664\n|title=Battle of Cassinga still rages |publisher=Independent Online |accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref> offering what was described as a \"swashbuckling\" front-line leadership, which won him the respect of many fellow [[Afrikaner]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/06/world/south-african-rightists-rally-behind-ex-generals.html |title=South African Rightists Rally Behind Ex-Generals |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=2009-04-29|first1=Bill|last1=Keller|date=1993-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nViljoen is credited by some with having made overtures which helped lead to [[white South African]]s' acceptance of universal suffrage and free elections, such as with his famous speech at the [[Broederbond]] annual assembly in [[Voortrekkerhoogte]], saying of the [[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black South African]]s in his army, ''As hulle kan veg vir Suid-Afrika, kan hulle stem vir Suid-Afrika!'' ([[Afrikaans]]: \"If they can fight for South Africa, then they can vote for South Africa!\").<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandela united a nation seeking national pride |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/weekend-argus-sunday-edition/20140511/281887296329149 |website=Pressreader |publisher=Weekend Argus (Sunday Edition) |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Viljoen and fellow retired generals formed the [[Afrikaner Volksfront]] (Afrikaner People's Front), an umbrella body for conservative Afrikaners. However, Viljoen reportedly had strained relationships with the leaders of other right-wing parties, who considered him too moderate.<ref>{{cite book|last=Waldmeir|first=Patti|title=Anatomy of a Miracle: The End of Apartheid and the Birth of the New South Africa|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2IHKD-FY8YgC|isbn=978-0-8135-2582-2|chapter=13: Battling for the Right|page=223}}</ref>\n\n===Bophuthatswana action and decision to contest elections===\n{{Main|Bophuthatswana coup d'\u00e9tat of 1994}}\nImmediately prior to the 1994 elections Viljoen had a force of between 50,000 and 60,000 trained paramilitary personnel at his command, with the ability to seize large sections of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=15&art_id=ct20021102190803396B510670&set_id=1|title=Soweto bombs may have been just a 'dry run'|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/990524/archive_001065.htm|title=Proving That One Man Can Make a Difference|publisher=US News & World Report|accessdate=2009-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013072623/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/990524/archive_001065.htm|archive-date=13 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The force was assembled in preparation for war with [[Umkhonto we Sizwe]], the military wing of the [[African National Congress]], as a potential contingency to protect Afrikaner interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?sf=13&set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20010324172513644P420166|title=Viljoen reveals just how close SA came to war|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1994, Viljoen led an effort by several thousand Volksfront militia to protect the [[bantustan]] president, [[Lucas Mangope]], in [[Bophuthatswana]] against a [[Bophuthatswana coup d'\u00e9tat of 1994|coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/11/world/homeland-leader-in-south-africa-flees-his-capital.html|title=Homeland Leader in South Africa Flees His Capital|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-11}}</ref> Despite being requested not to participate in the action because of extremist views, militants of the [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging]] also advanced into Bophuthatswana, sparking clashes with the security forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/12/world/mixed-signals-fatal-for-south-african-separatists.html|title=Mixed Signals Fatal for South African Separatists|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-12}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after the incident, Viljoen split from the Volksfront<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940313&slug=1899838|title=South Africa Takes Control Of Homeland \u2013 Bophuthatswana's Ruler Removed To Open Up Election|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Tom| last=Cohen| date=1994-03-13}}</ref> and initiated a legitimate election campaign,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/13/world/a-homeland-s-agony.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2|title=A Homeland's Agony|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-29| first=Bill| last=Keller| date=1994-03-13}}</ref> co-founding and becoming leader of the [[Freedom Front]] (''Vryheidsfront''), a new political party representing white conservatives. His decision to take part in the elections is believed to have prevented armed resistance by the far right and on the occasion of his retirement from politics, the South African government recognised him for preventing bloodshed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_996781,00.html|title=Mbeki thanks Constand Viljoen|publisher=News24|accessdate=2009-04-29}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nViljoen's decision was at least partly influenced by the mediation of his identical twin brother, [[Abraham Viljoen]] (Braam), who was an anti-apartheid activist while his brother led the military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1993/1028/28131.html|title=Abraham Viljoen: Longtime Campaigner For Black-White Solidarity in South Africa|publisher=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unisa.ac.za/default.asp?Cmd=ViewContent&ContentID=14555|title=Mediation during the Transition in South Afric|publisher=University of South Africa|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Post-apartheid South Africa===\nIn [[1994 South African general election|the election]], the Freedom Front, under the leadership of Viljoen, received 2.2% of the national vote and nine seats in the National Assembly. It became the strongest party outside [[Nelson Mandela]]'s Government of National Unity. Although his supporters were at odds with the government and the ANC, Viljoen praised Mandela on the occasion of his retreat from politics in 1999, even ending his Parliamentary speech speaking in Mandela's native language, [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]: ''Go rest in peace. Go rest in the shadow of a tree at your home''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Foes pay tribute as Mandela begins long goodbye |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/27/nelsonmandela |accessdate=3 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 March 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Viljoen handed over the leadership of the Freedom Front to [[Pieter Mulder]] and retired from politics, citing his frustration working with a parliament dominated by the ANC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/1223061.stm|title=Constand Viljoen to leave SA parliament|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-04-29| date=2001-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==After retirement==\nIn 2003, it emerged that Viljoen had been a target of the [[Boeremag]] paramilitary right-wing group, which considered him a traitor who had underhandedly sold out the Afrikaner people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=qw1067593321550B263|title=Was the TAU part of the Boeremag plot?|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Viljoen, aged 74, put up what was described as a spirited fight against two would-be muggers, who were subsequently arrested.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/ex-sandf-chief-turns-table-on-muggers-1.400904#.UXGgNsoYq9s|title=Ex-SANDF chief turns tables on muggers|publisher=IOL News|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>\n==Death==\nCurrent Freedom Front Plus leader [[Pieter Groenewald]] announced on 3 April 2020 that Viljoen had died on his farm in [[Ohrigstad]], [[Limpopo]]. He was 86 and was surrounded by his children. Viljoen died of natural causes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Toit |first1=Pieter |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-general-constand-viljoen-former-sadf-commander-and-political-leader-dies-at-86-20200403 |title=General Constand Viljoen, former SADF commander and political leader, dies at 86 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |agency=News24 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe is survived by his wife Christina Susanna Heckroodt, four sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite news |title=General Constand Viljoen passes away aged 86 |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-general-constand-viljoen-former-sadf-commander-and-political-leader-dies-at-86-20200403 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n* {{Medal Display|SSAG}}\n* {{Medal Display|SD}}\n* {{Medal Display|SOE}}\n* {{Medal Display|SM52}}\n* {{Medal Display|MMM}}\n* {{Medal Display|PP}}\n* {{Medal Display|GoodServiceG}}\n* {{Medal Display|GoodServiceS}}\n* {{Medal Display|PFGS}}\n* {{Medal Display|ORB2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new | reason =  New Party}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus|Freedom Front]] | years = 1994\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft | after = Dr [[Pieter Mulder]]  }}\n|-\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Magnus Malan]] |rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Chief of the [[South African Defence Force]]| | years = 1980\u20131985}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Johannes Geldenhuys]] |rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = Chief of the [[South African Army]]| | years = 1976\u20131980}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = JW van Niekerk}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Officer Commanding [[South African Army College]]| | years = 1968\u20131969}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Johan Potgieter]] }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Hendrik Greyvenstein]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Officer Commanding [[School of Artillery (South Africa)|School of Artillery]]| | years = 1966\u20131968}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Shorty Brown]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Helm Roos]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[School of Artillery (South Africa)|Chief Instructor Gunnery]]| | years = 1962\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft | after = John Albert Reid Cox}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SA Defence Chiefs}}\n{{SA Army Chiefs}}{{Freedom Front Plus}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Viljoen, Constand}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Krugersdorp]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:South African anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of the South African Army]]\n[[Category:South African military personnel of the Border War]]\n[[Category:Freedom Front Plus politicians]]\n", "name_user": "41.115.34.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Date of death)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constand_Viljoen"}
{"title_page": "Edward C. Corrigan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Edward Corrigan\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_place   = [[Saint-Jean-Chrysostome, Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie, Quebec| Saint-Jean-Chrysostome, Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie, Quebec]],<br> [[Canada]]\n| birth_date  =  {{birth date|1843|05|24}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1924|07|04|1843|05|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Kansas City, Missouri]],<br>[[United States]]\n| resting_place      = \n| occupation    = Racetrack owner, racehorse owner, breeder, trainer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \"[[Hawthorne Race Course|Master of Hawthorne]]\"<br>[[American Derby|1884 American Derby]]<br>[[1890 Kentucky Derby]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward C. Corrigan''' (May 24, 1843 - July 4, 1924) was a [[Canada|Canadian-born]] racetrack proprietor, racehorse owner/breeder and trainer in American [[Thoroughbred racing]] whose ''[[New York Times]]'' obituary called him a \"Once Powerful Turf Figure\" and along with ''[[The San Francisco Examiner]]'', the ''[[Chicago American|Chicago Examiner]]'' and other U.S. newspapers regularly referred to him as the \"Master of Hawthorne\" for his role as the founder of [[Hawthorne Race Course]] which opened in [[Cicero, Illinois]] in 1891. Corrigan was the [[1890 Kentucky Derby]] winning owner and trainer and in a 1911 article on Derby history the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'' wrote that Edward Corrigan was \"the man who at one time controlled more racing property and owned a greater stable of horses than any other turfman of his time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1924/07/05/archives/edward-corrigan-dies-at-age-of-82-master-of-hawthorne-once-powerful.html |title=Edward Corrigan Dies At Age 82 |publisher=New York Times |date=1924-07-05 |accessdate=2019-06-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.chipublib.org/digital/collection/examiner/id/8224/ |title= Corrigan \"Broke\" Loses Racetrack |publisher=The San Francisco Examiner |date=1909-05-20 |accessdate=2019-06-16}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.chipublib.org/digital/collection/examiner/id/8224/ |title=Corrigan \"Broke\" Loses Racetrack |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1909-05-20 |accessdate=2019-06-16}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentuckyderby.com/history/kentucky-derby-winners |title=Kentucky Derby Winners |publisher=Churchill Downs Incorporated |date=2019-06-16 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1911043001/drf1911043001_1_4  |title=Successful Trainers in Kentucky's Foremost Race |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1911-04-30 |accessdate=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corrigan, Edward C.}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:American horse racing industry executives]]\n[[Category:American racehorse owners and breeders]]\n[[Category:American horse trainers]]\n[[Category:Owners of Kentucky Derby winners]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00e9vis, Quebec]]\n\n{{Horseracing-bio-stub}}\n{{Canada-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Edward Corrigan\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_place   = [[Saint-Jean-Chrysostome, Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie, Quebec| Saint-Jean-Chrysostome, Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie, Quebec]],<br> [[Canada]]\n| birth_date  =  {{birth date|1843|05|24}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1924|07|04|1843|05|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Kansas City, Missouri]],<br>[[United States]]\n| resting_place      = \n| occupation    = Racetrack owner, racehorse owner, breeder, trainer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \"[[Hawthorne Race Course|Master of Hawthorne]]\"<br>[[American Derby|1884 American Derby]]<br>[[Kentucky Derby|1890 Kentucky Derby]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward C. Corrigan''' (May 24, 1843 - July 4, 1924) was a [[Canada|Canadian-born]] racetrack proprietor, racehorse owner/breeder and trainer in American [[Thoroughbred racing]] whose ''[[New York Times]]'' obituary called him a \"Once Powerful Turf Figure\" and along with ''[[The San Francisco Examiner]]'', the ''[[Chicago American|Chicago Examiner]]'' and other U.S. newspapers regularly referred to him as the \"Master of Hawthorne\" for his role as the founder of [[Hawthorne Race Course]] which opened in [[Cicero, Illinois]] in 1891. Corrigan was the [[1890 Kentucky Derby]] winning owner and trainer and in a 1911 article on Derby history the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'' wrote that Edward Corrigan was \"the man who at one time controlled more racing property and owned a greater stable of horses than any other turfman of his time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1924/07/05/archives/edward-corrigan-dies-at-age-of-82-master-of-hawthorne-once-powerful.html |title=Edward Corrigan Dies At Age 82 |publisher=New York Times |date=1924-07-05 |accessdate=2019-06-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.chipublib.org/digital/collection/examiner/id/8224/ |title= Corrigan \"Broke\" Loses Racetrack |publisher=The San Francisco Examiner |date=1909-05-20 |accessdate=2019-06-16}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.chipublib.org/digital/collection/examiner/id/8224/ |title=Corrigan \"Broke\" Loses Racetrack |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1909-05-20 |accessdate=2019-06-16}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentuckyderby.com/history/kentucky-derby-winners |title=Kentucky Derby Winners |publisher=Churchill Downs Incorporated |date=2019-06-16 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1911043001/drf1911043001_1_4  |title=Successful Trainers in Kentucky's Foremost Race |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1911-04-30 |accessdate=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corrigan, Edward C.}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:American horse racing industry executives]]\n[[Category:American racehorse owners and breeders]]\n[[Category:American horse trainers]]\n[[Category:Owners of Kentucky Derby winners]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00e9vis, Quebec]]\n\n{{Horseracing-bio-stub}}\n{{Canada-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Stretchrunner", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_C._Corrigan"}
